WEBVTT

00:06.000 --> 00:12.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:58.760 --> 01:00.751
(CONFESSION ROOM
WINDOW SLIDES OPEN)

01:04.120 --> 01:06.270
Bless me, Father,
for I have sinned.

01:08.080 --> 01:10.992
It's been, uh,
24 hours since my last confession.

01:11.320 --> 01:13.675
Son, it's so late.

01:13.800 --> 01:16.598
Yeah, Father.
Work has just...

01:17.240 --> 01:18.240
(SIGHS)

01:23.520 --> 01:26.671
I lied to Connie.
Uh, to my wife.

01:28.160 --> 01:29.434
This is
very serious.

01:29.520 --> 01:30.669
I know.

01:31.600 --> 01:32.919
I promised her
I'd quit smoking.

01:33.000 --> 01:34.080
She thinks it's bad for me.

01:34.120 --> 01:36.315
And I'm trying, but...

01:37.440 --> 01:39.908
I snuck a couple
of cigarettes.

01:40.520 --> 01:41.953
Maybe three.

01:42.080 --> 01:43.752
(THUNDER RUMBLING AT DISTANCE)

01:44.520 --> 01:45.669
Yes.

01:46.440 --> 01:47.668
It's so hard.

01:48.600 --> 01:49.794
Yes.

01:51.040 --> 01:52.632
But I'm trying.

01:54.280 --> 01:56.032
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

02:09.199 --> 02:11.156
NARRATOR: It is 5:00 a.m.

02:11.360 --> 02:14.511
Still shank of night for some.

02:15.400 --> 02:16.435
(CAMERA CLICKING AT DISTANCE)

02:16.520 --> 02:20.559
But for Eddie Mannix,
beginning of a new work day.

02:24.400 --> 02:28.791
The movie studio for which he
works manufactures stories,

02:29.560 --> 02:33.838
each its own day-lit drama or
moonlit dream. (WOMAN LAUGHING)

02:34.400 --> 02:38.029
But the work of Eddie Mannix
cares not for day or night.

02:38.120 --> 02:39.712
(WOMAN EXCLAIMING)

02:40.360 --> 02:42.510
And cares little for his rest.

02:43.600 --> 02:47.149
PHOTOGRAPHER: That's right, doll face.
Churn that butter for me.

02:47.240 --> 02:48.240
Atta girl.

02:50.160 --> 02:52.515
Oh, Jesus Christ
on a scooter!

02:52.600 --> 02:53.635
You here?

02:54.280 --> 02:56.510
EDDIE: The studio has the rights
to Gloria's likeness, Falco.

02:56.600 --> 02:58.272
Give me the negatives and
things will go easier on you.

02:58.360 --> 02:59.759
These are for
private use, Eddie.

02:59.920 --> 03:01.035
Come on.

03:02.800 --> 03:03.800
Oh, boy.

03:05.440 --> 03:08.113
Can't a girl take a few pictures,
have a few laughs?

03:08.280 --> 03:11.272
Jeez, Eddie!
What an old stick in the mud.

03:12.400 --> 03:13.400
(GASPS)

03:13.520 --> 03:14.669
Now, you listen to me.

03:14.880 --> 03:16.560
You were at a party,
had too much to drink.

03:16.640 --> 03:18.870
Somebody brought you here,
you don't remember who.

03:18.960 --> 03:20.313
You're going home now.

03:20.400 --> 03:22.356
Your name's
Mary Jo Scheinbrotte.

03:22.480 --> 03:24.240
(SOBBING) Okay, Eddie.
COP: So, Eddie Mannix.

03:25.280 --> 03:26.474
Saw your heap outside.

03:26.680 --> 03:29.035
Got a call.
Loud, disorderly.

03:29.200 --> 03:31.270
Possible French
postcard situation.

03:31.480 --> 03:32.754
Someone was
pulling your leg.

03:32.840 --> 03:34.796
Mary Jo here was just
at a costume party.

03:34.960 --> 03:36.552
It's not really
her dirndl.

03:36.720 --> 03:38.880
She wants to contribute
something to your pension fund.

03:39.320 --> 03:40.799
Sorry to drag you
out in the rain.

03:40.960 --> 03:42.791
Well, say,
no problem at all.

03:43.240 --> 03:44.719
Aren't you
Gloria DeLamour?

03:44.880 --> 03:45.949
No, no,
I'm Mary Jo

03:46.160 --> 03:47.195
something.

03:47.360 --> 03:48.554
Scheinbrotte.

03:48.640 --> 03:49.640
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

03:51.520 --> 03:52.919
Say, Brian.

03:55.800 --> 03:57.677
Can I bum a cigarette?

03:59.560 --> 04:01.152
(SOLDIERS MARCHING)

04:01.320 --> 04:03.959
NARRATOR: Ancient Rome.

04:04.040 --> 04:08.875
Twelve years into the rule
of Tiberius, Ruler Maximus.

04:09.040 --> 04:12.828
Rome's legions are
masters of the world.

04:13.000 --> 04:15.389
The stomp of its
sandals heard from

04:15.520 --> 04:17.909
the Iberian
Peninsula in the west,

04:18.079 --> 04:22.358
through the halls of the great
library of Alexandria in the east.

04:23.200 --> 04:27.512
As oppressed people everywhere
writhe under the Roman lash,

04:27.680 --> 04:32.515
freeman and vassal are united
in one compulsory worship.

04:33.040 --> 04:34.040
(GRUNTS)

04:34.280 --> 04:37.556
The emperor,
Caesar, is Godhead.

04:37.720 --> 04:40.393
Lord of every man 's
body and spirit.

04:41.600 --> 04:43.192
For those who will not submit,

04:43.360 --> 04:47.717
the galleys, the arenas,
even crucifixion await.

04:48.880 --> 04:52.316
But there is a new wind
blowing from the east,

04:52.400 --> 04:54.516
from the dusty streets
of Bethlehem,

04:54.600 --> 04:58.275
that will soon challenge
the vast house of Caesar,

04:58.400 --> 05:02.075
that edifice wrought
of brick and blood

05:02.160 --> 05:04.958
which now seems so secure.

05:33.600 --> 05:34.600
(HORSE SNORTS)

05:38.840 --> 05:39.840
Ha!

05:44.280 --> 05:45.998
There she is, Gracchus.

05:46.640 --> 05:48.358
Ah, what a beauty.

05:48.760 --> 05:50.830
GRACCHUS: Aye,
Autolochus. Rome.

05:51.280 --> 05:54.829
Suckled by a she-wolf and
nurturing us, her sons, in turn.

05:54.920 --> 05:56.672
Tonight I bathe in Caracalla

05:56.760 --> 06:01.754
and wash away the dust
of 300 miles of Frankish road.

06:02.280 --> 06:03.429
To Rome.

06:04.040 --> 06:05.189
To Rome!
(HORSE NEIGHING)

06:05.800 --> 06:07.631
NARRATOR: Yes, to Rome!

06:07.840 --> 06:11.150
Glorious center
of Caesar's rule.

06:12.800 --> 06:17.316
But far away in Palestine,
another man is coming home.

06:17.520 --> 06:21.035
Saul, humble
merchant of Tarsus

06:21.120 --> 06:24.954
is about to be
struck down by a vision.

06:26.120 --> 06:28.793
What thing is this?

06:38.320 --> 06:40.151
NATALIE: Gloria DeLamour
has been checked into

06:40.280 --> 06:42.430
Our Lady of Perpetual Rest to dry out.
EDDIE: Uh-huh.

06:42.520 --> 06:45.080
NATALIE: You have a 10:00 a.m.
with Monsignor O'Reilly

06:45.160 --> 06:47.037
at the Wallace
Beery Conference Room,

06:47.640 --> 06:48.789
and he's bringing
in a Lester Silkwood

06:48.880 --> 06:50.518
from the Legion of
Catholic Decency.

06:50.720 --> 06:54.076
And we've also invited Patriarch
Vlassos for the Eastern view.

06:54.240 --> 06:55.673
Have they read the script?
Roger.

06:55.840 --> 06:57.910
Let's also invite a rabbi and a
Protestant padre of some sort

06:58.000 --> 06:59.194
so we can get
everybody's two cents.

06:59.280 --> 07:00.280
Check.

07:00.360 --> 07:01.873
How's production on Tucumcari?

07:02.040 --> 07:03.598
Principal is
on schedule,

07:03.760 --> 07:05.034
but second unit
has been idle

07:05.120 --> 07:06.633
in Gallup, New Mexico
for four days.

07:06.720 --> 07:07.789
Heavy rain.

07:07.880 --> 07:09.472
Forecast?
Not good.

07:09.560 --> 07:10.560
Send an insert truck,

07:10.640 --> 07:11.993
have them shoot driving
plates for Came the Rain.

07:12.080 --> 07:13.195
Check.

07:13.280 --> 07:14.679
Jonah's Daughter
still behind?

07:14.760 --> 07:16.910
Yes. Uh, director says
the problem is DeeAnna,

07:17.040 --> 07:18.439
and she's
getting worse.

07:18.520 --> 07:21.034
I know what it is.
I'll drop in on her after my 10 o'clock.

07:21.120 --> 07:22.439
All right,
let's call New York.

07:22.680 --> 07:25.280
(LINE BUZZES) NATALIE (ON INTERCOM)
Mr. Schenk's office, line two.

07:26.040 --> 07:28.349
Hi, Dorothy. Eddie Mannix.
The old man in?

07:30.080 --> 07:31.354
Natalie, I want
the box office

07:31.440 --> 07:33.635
on The Debonaires
and on Blessed Event.

07:33.720 --> 07:37.076
Can you also...
Yes! Good morning, Mr. Schenk.

07:37.240 --> 07:38.912
Very well.
Thank you.

07:40.240 --> 07:42.196
Proceeding.
You know, proceeding.

07:42.360 --> 07:44.635
Yeah, Merrily We Dance
starts shooting today.

07:44.800 --> 07:46.119
Beardly Auberon
gave us a draft

07:46.200 --> 07:47.394
that's extremely classy.

07:47.560 --> 07:49.039
Joan Van Vechten's
playing Dierdre,

07:49.120 --> 07:50.840
but we need a male lead
and we need him now.

07:52.040 --> 07:54.508
No, Jack Hogarth is
drying out at Cedars.

07:55.920 --> 07:57.239
Metro won't lend us Gable

07:57.320 --> 07:58.840
unless we give them
the Comiskey twins.

07:59.400 --> 08:01.470
Of course not.
I agree.

08:02.720 --> 08:04.631
What?

08:04.800 --> 08:06.756
Hobie Doyle? Do you
really think so?

08:06.960 --> 08:08.473
After all,
he's a dust actor.

08:08.560 --> 08:10.915
The man barely
knows how to talk.

08:12.560 --> 08:14.198
Yes, of course,
Mr. Schenk, I agree,

08:14.280 --> 08:16.271
but I don't know
if Hobie Doyle

08:16.360 --> 08:18.590
has the (STUTTERS) poise
in a dinner jacket.

08:20.120 --> 08:21.599
Yes, we do need
someone pronto.

08:23.440 --> 08:24.919
No, I don't,
that's very true.

08:25.080 --> 08:26.911
But let me talk to Laurence Laurentz,
the director.

08:27.080 --> 08:28.593
It could work.
It could work.

08:28.760 --> 08:30.796
Hobie Doyle is
a very promising idea.

08:37.640 --> 08:38.640
(GRUNTS)

08:39.280 --> 08:40.280
(GUNSHOT)

08:43.679 --> 08:45.318
(MEN GRUNTING)

08:48.720 --> 08:49.720
(WHISTLES)

08:49.840 --> 08:51.114
HOBIE: Whitey!

09:00.640 --> 09:02.198
(GUNSHOTS)

09:04.640 --> 09:07.473
(GUNSHOTS CONTINUE)

09:18.760 --> 09:19.760
(WHISTLES)

09:21.320 --> 09:22.320
(WHINNYING)

09:23.880 --> 09:25.393
DIRECTOR: And cut!

09:25.560 --> 09:26.788
Great, Hobie.

09:27.200 --> 09:28.713
I can do the
handstand smoother

09:28.800 --> 09:30.313
if you give me
another shot at her.

09:30.480 --> 09:33.313
We got four good ones, Hobie,
and Whitey's tired.

09:33.480 --> 09:35.391
Okay, you're
the boss man.

09:35.480 --> 09:37.550
If that's lunch, I'm gonna
grab me a plate of beans.

09:58.040 --> 09:59.996
(BEVERAGE FIZZING)

10:05.360 --> 10:07.032
All right, kids,
this is Rome.

10:07.120 --> 10:08.840
You're over at this
guy's house for a revel.

10:09.040 --> 10:10.519
And in comes Antoninus.

10:10.680 --> 10:12.636
Lots of energy.

10:14.520 --> 10:16.476
What are you doing at
the table of viands?

10:16.920 --> 10:18.433
Huh? You're supposed to be
reclining with the lyre.

10:18.520 --> 10:19.669
I'm sorry,
I was just...

10:19.760 --> 10:20.829
Recline with the lyre.

10:22.200 --> 10:24.350
Don't sit on the
pediment. Recline.

10:24.560 --> 10:25.754
Relaxed, festive.

10:25.920 --> 10:27.672
CREW MEMBER: Extras set?
Set!

10:27.760 --> 10:28.829
CREW MEMBER: Roll sound!

10:28.920 --> 10:29.955
I got my eye on you.

10:30.040 --> 10:31.598
CREW MEMBER:
Roll camera. Fountain!

10:32.240 --> 10:33.309
(BELL RINGING)

10:33.400 --> 10:35.197
Hail, Caesar!
Ten-apple, take 10.

10:35.720 --> 10:37.278
DIRECTOR: And action!

10:38.720 --> 10:39.720
(HARP PLAYING)

10:42.800 --> 10:44.233
SENATOR SESTIMUS: Autolochus!

10:44.320 --> 10:47.312
I had heard rumors
of your return to Rome.

10:48.080 --> 10:50.435
(HARP PLAYS OUT OF TUNE) AUTOLOCHUS:
More than rumors, noble Sestimus.

10:50.600 --> 10:53.319
I see that you are the same
worshipper of Bacchus.

10:53.560 --> 10:54.754
What gaiety.

10:55.120 --> 10:57.031
There is still
truth in the adage

10:57.120 --> 10:58.633
"What pleasures
cannot be found

10:58.760 --> 11:00.239
"in the villa of
Sestimus Amydias

11:00.400 --> 11:01.549
"cannot be
found in Rome!"

11:01.920 --> 11:02.920
(ALL LAUGHING)

11:03.400 --> 11:04.515
But seriously,

11:04.640 --> 11:06.949
there is talk the Senate will
send our legions out again,

11:07.120 --> 11:09.953
and this time not on
a short march to Gaul.

11:10.920 --> 11:13.354
What truth to these
mutterings, Sestimus?

11:13.600 --> 11:16.478
The matter has been
taken up in the Senate.

11:16.920 --> 11:20.276
It seems that there
is unrest in Palestine.

11:20.640 --> 11:21.640
Palestine?

11:22.000 --> 11:23.000
(SIGHS)
That backwater!

11:23.760 --> 11:25.432
They'll hardly be
sending the sixth legion

11:25.520 --> 11:28.751
to that godforsaken
patch of desert!

11:28.840 --> 11:30.637
(ALL LAUGHING)

11:31.760 --> 11:32.954
MAN: Palestine!

11:36.880 --> 11:38.199
WOMAN:
(CHUCKLING) Palestine!

11:45.160 --> 11:46.160
Ah.

11:47.960 --> 11:49.712
Holding for
a dissolve...

11:50.040 --> 11:51.758
Still laughing...

11:52.960 --> 11:54.518
Holding...

11:55.520 --> 11:56.520
And cut!

11:57.640 --> 11:59.119
Fine, boys.
That was just fine.

11:59.320 --> 12:00.469
BAIRD: Was I okay?
Was I all right?

12:00.640 --> 12:01.629
(BELL RINGING)
CREW MEMBER: That's a cut!

12:01.720 --> 12:02.948
DIRECTOR: We're gonna
move on to the brazier scene.

12:03.040 --> 12:05.031
Was I all right with the "mutterings"?
It felt a little...

12:05.160 --> 12:06.434
No, no, no, no,
it's fine.

12:06.520 --> 12:08.158
Moving on,
brazier scene, 20 minutes.

12:08.240 --> 12:09.434
Popping over
to the trailer.

12:09.520 --> 12:10.669
Okay. In the
brazier scene,

12:10.760 --> 12:13.035
they changed
"passion" to "ardor."

12:13.200 --> 12:15.998
What? Why?
I liked "passion."

12:16.080 --> 12:18.389
It's strong.
It's passion!

12:22.520 --> 12:26.672
BAIRD: "Such is my greeting after
three months' sojourn in Gaul?

12:27.080 --> 12:29.833
"Not so, Ursulina."

12:30.360 --> 12:32.510
(GROANING)

12:33.440 --> 12:35.158
"My ardor...

12:36.520 --> 12:38.988
"My ardor is yet as warm

12:39.080 --> 12:41.355
"as the embers
of this brazier.

12:41.520 --> 12:43.078
BAIRD: "Embers
of this brazier."

12:44.280 --> 12:45.508
We're ready for you,
Mr. Whitlock!

12:45.600 --> 12:47.670
BAIRD: "Not so,
Sperm-ulina."

12:50.760 --> 12:52.352
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

12:55.520 --> 12:56.520
(GRUNTS)

12:57.080 --> 12:58.760
EDDIE: Gentlemen,
thank you all for coming.

12:58.880 --> 13:00.632
I know you have parishes,
flocks and temples

13:00.800 --> 13:02.518
making enormous
demands on your time.

13:02.680 --> 13:03.795
But I'm sure you
appreciate also

13:03.880 --> 13:05.359
that great masses
of humanity

13:05.520 --> 13:08.273
look to pictures for
information and uplift

13:08.440 --> 13:10.556
and, yes, entertainment.

13:11.040 --> 13:13.110
Now, here at Capitol Pictures,
as you know,

13:13.280 --> 13:16.795
an army of technicians and actors
and top-notch artistic people

13:16.960 --> 13:20.191
are working hard to bring to the
screen the story of the Christ.

13:20.400 --> 13:21.719
It's a swell story.

13:21.880 --> 13:23.472
A story told before, yes,

13:23.640 --> 13:24.755
but we like to
flatter ourselves

13:24.840 --> 13:25.875
that it's never been told

13:26.040 --> 13:27.917
with this kind of
distinction and panache.

13:28.080 --> 13:31.390
Perhaps, sir, you forget its
telling in the Holy Bible.

13:31.560 --> 13:34.028
Quite right, Patriarch.
The Bible, of course, is terrific.

13:34.120 --> 13:35.712
But for
millions of people,

13:35.880 --> 13:38.758
pictures will be their
reference point for the story.

13:38.880 --> 13:42.236
The story's embodiment,
the story's, uh...

13:42.320 --> 13:45.073
Realization.

13:45.160 --> 13:48.311
You "realize," of course,
that for we Jews,

13:48.400 --> 13:52.234
any visual depiction of the Godhead
is most strictly prohibited.

13:52.640 --> 13:53.640
Oh.

13:54.320 --> 13:57.756
But, of course, for us, the man
Jesus Nazarene is not God.

13:57.920 --> 13:58.920
A-ha!

13:59.240 --> 14:00.753
Who plays Christ?

14:00.920 --> 14:02.638
Oh, a kid we're all
very excited about.

14:02.720 --> 14:03.835
Todd Hocheiser.

14:03.920 --> 14:07.469
Wonderful young actor we found in Akron,
Ohio, in a nationwide talent hunt.

14:07.640 --> 14:09.551
But Hocheiser is
seen only fleetingly

14:09.640 --> 14:11.198
and with extreme taste.

14:11.360 --> 14:14.511
Our story is told through the
eyes of a Roman tribune.

14:14.680 --> 14:16.750
Autolochus Antoninus.

14:16.960 --> 14:19.269
Ordinary man,
skeptical at first,

14:19.440 --> 14:21.112
but who comes to
a grudging respect

14:21.280 --> 14:22.952
for this swell
figure from the East.

14:23.280 --> 14:25.635
And Autolochus
is played by

14:26.360 --> 14:27.952
Baird Whitlock.

14:28.440 --> 14:29.440
Oh, my.

14:30.000 --> 14:32.434
Well, he is certainly
a great talent.

14:32.640 --> 14:34.240
Now, Hail, Caesar!
Is a prestige picture,

14:34.320 --> 14:35.799
our biggest
release of the year,

14:35.960 --> 14:38.235
and we're devoting huge
resources to its production

14:38.320 --> 14:39.594
in order to
make it first-class

14:39.680 --> 14:40.715
in every respect.

14:40.880 --> 14:43.189
Gentlemen, given
its enormous expense,

14:43.400 --> 14:45.311
we don't wanna send it to
market except in the certainty

14:45.480 --> 14:47.914
that it will not offend
any reasonable American

14:48.000 --> 14:50.389
regardless of faith or creed.

14:50.480 --> 14:52.789
Now that's where you come in.
You've read the script.

14:52.880 --> 14:54.960
I wanna know if the theological
elements of the story

14:55.080 --> 14:56.080
are up to snuff.

14:56.240 --> 14:58.310
I thought the
chariot scene was fakey.

14:58.480 --> 15:00.560
How is he going to jump from
one chariot to the other

15:00.640 --> 15:02.312
going full speed?

15:04.640 --> 15:05.640
Uh-huh.

15:05.680 --> 15:07.796
Well, we can look at that.

15:08.160 --> 15:10.913
But as for the
religious aspect,

15:11.000 --> 15:13.594
does the depiction of Christ
Jesus cut the mustard?

15:14.320 --> 15:16.151
Well, the nature of Christ
is not quite as simple

15:16.240 --> 15:17.719
as your photoplay
would have it.

15:17.880 --> 15:18.915
How so, Father?

15:19.000 --> 15:22.231
It's not the case simply
that Christ is God, or God Christ.

15:22.440 --> 15:23.509
You can say
that again.

15:23.600 --> 15:25.033
The Nazarene
was not God.

15:25.200 --> 15:26.349
He was not not-God.

15:26.440 --> 15:27.600
RABBI: He was a man.
Part God.

15:27.680 --> 15:28.749
RABBI: No, sir.

15:28.840 --> 15:30.831
But, Rabbi, all of us have a
little bit of God in us, don't we?

15:30.920 --> 15:31.920
Well...

15:32.000 --> 15:33.752
It's the foundation
of our belief

15:33.840 --> 15:37.674
that Christ is most properly
referred to as the Son of God.

15:37.920 --> 15:41.515
It's the Son of God who takes the
sins of the world upon himself

15:42.200 --> 15:46.955
so that the rest of God's children,
we imperfect beings,

15:47.120 --> 15:50.430
through faith, may enter
the Kingdom of heaven.

15:51.720 --> 15:54.188
So God is split?
CATHOLIC CLERGYMAN: Yes.

15:54.880 --> 15:56.029
And no.

15:56.120 --> 15:57.678
EASTERN ORTHODOX CLERGYMAN:
There is unity in division.

15:57.760 --> 15:59.113
And division
in unity.

15:59.280 --> 16:00.554
I'm not sure
I follow, Padre.

16:00.720 --> 16:02.800
Young man, you don't follow
for a very simple reason.

16:02.960 --> 16:04.109
These men
are screwballs.

16:04.280 --> 16:06.271
RABBI: God has children?
What, and a dog?

16:06.800 --> 16:08.028
A collie, maybe?

16:08.120 --> 16:09.314
God doesn't
have children.

16:09.400 --> 16:11.118
He's a bachelor.
And very angry.

16:11.240 --> 16:12.320
No, no, he used
to be angry.

16:12.400 --> 16:13.400
What?
He got over it?

16:13.560 --> 16:14.920
You worship the God
of another age.

16:15.080 --> 16:16.229
Who has no love.

16:16.400 --> 16:17.879
Not true.
He likes Jews.

16:18.080 --> 16:19.149
God loves everyone.

16:19.240 --> 16:20.355
God is love!

16:21.080 --> 16:22.195
God is who he is.

16:22.280 --> 16:24.032
This is special?
Who isn't who is?

16:24.120 --> 16:27.078
But how should God be
rendered in a motion picture?

16:27.240 --> 16:28.559
God isn't in the
motion picture!

16:28.720 --> 16:30.073
Then who is
Todd Hocheiser?

16:30.240 --> 16:32.754
Gentlemen, maybe we're biting off
more than we can chew.

16:32.920 --> 16:35.150
We don't need to agree on
the nature of the deity here,

16:35.320 --> 16:38.995
if we could focus on the Christ,
whatever his parentage.

16:39.160 --> 16:42.391
My question is,
is our depiction fair?

16:42.600 --> 16:43.794
I have seen worse.

16:43.880 --> 16:44.915
Reverend?

16:45.160 --> 16:47.958
There is nothing to
offend a reasonable man.

16:48.040 --> 16:49.075
EDDIE: Father.

16:49.160 --> 16:51.958
CATHOLIC CLERGYMAN: The motion picture
teleplay was respectful

16:52.040 --> 16:54.873
and exhibited
tastefulness and class.

16:54.960 --> 16:56.678
Who made you an expert
all of a sudden?

16:58.520 --> 17:00.112
And what do
you think, Rabbi?

17:00.440 --> 17:01.440
Eh...

17:01.640 --> 17:03.437
I haven't
an opinion.

17:03.960 --> 17:05.393
How did we do?
I don't...

17:05.480 --> 17:06.959
Fine. What's up?

17:07.119 --> 17:09.031
Can't find
Baird Whitlock.

17:09.200 --> 17:10.234
He left the set
over an hour ago,

17:10.319 --> 17:11.958
said he was going
to his dressing room,

17:12.040 --> 17:13.189
but he isn't there.

17:13.280 --> 17:15.349
Out on a bender? Middle of the day?
Am I crazy?

17:15.440 --> 17:17.192
You're not crazy,
but, no.

17:17.359 --> 17:20.715
I checked the Til Two, Dan Tana's,
Rusty Scupper. No soap.

17:20.800 --> 17:22.279
Home, maybe? Called his wife?
Yep.

17:22.440 --> 17:23.440
What did Laura say?

17:23.560 --> 17:24.800
"He's not home,
he's never home.

17:24.880 --> 17:26.233
"He's a louse.
Try one of his chippies."

17:26.319 --> 17:27.752
Called that script girl,
what's her name, Francie?

17:27.839 --> 17:28.875
Uh, check.

17:28.960 --> 17:29.995
Any of the gals
missing from the set?

17:30.080 --> 17:31.080
Nope.

17:31.240 --> 17:34.118
EDDIE: All right, gone an hour?
We won't worry yet.

17:40.400 --> 17:41.435
STUDIO ASSISTANT: Hobie?

17:42.200 --> 17:44.031
The studio says
you're finished here,

17:44.120 --> 17:45.838
and you're to report
back to the lot.

17:45.960 --> 17:46.995
How come?

17:47.160 --> 17:48.513
They're changing
your image.

17:48.680 --> 17:49.715
Okay.

17:49.920 --> 17:52.275
And the studio says you're
escorting Carlotta Valdez

17:52.360 --> 17:53.759
to your premiere tonight.

17:54.480 --> 17:55.913
How come?
I don't know her.

17:56.000 --> 17:58.798
The studio's arranging it.
They're changing your image.

18:38.520 --> 18:40.192
(WOMAN SINGING OPERATICALLY)

20:27.480 --> 20:29.198
(DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)

20:31.080 --> 20:32.080
(GONG RINGS)

20:46.920 --> 20:48.114
Damn it!

20:51.320 --> 20:52.320
(MUSIC STOPS)

20:54.920 --> 20:55.920
(DRESS STRAINING)

20:57.960 --> 20:58.960
(GRUNTS)

20:59.680 --> 21:00.680
(DRESS POPS)

21:03.120 --> 21:04.951
You have gas
again, ma'am?

21:05.120 --> 21:07.236
Ma'am? Miss.
Do I look married?

21:07.400 --> 21:09.516
No, miss.
No! Yeah, "Gas again."

21:10.000 --> 21:11.399
Ask him. He knows.

21:11.560 --> 21:12.913
All right. Scram.

21:13.840 --> 21:15.193
How are you,
DeeAnna?

21:15.920 --> 21:17.990
How am I? Wet.

21:18.080 --> 21:20.480
I don't think I'm gonna fit in
that fish-ass after this week.

21:20.560 --> 21:22.596
Oh, we should have the water
ballet in the can after tomorrow.

21:22.680 --> 21:23.795
In the nightclub scene,

21:23.880 --> 21:26.440
wardrobe will have a gown for
you that's more forgiving.

21:28.280 --> 21:30.000
Any more thoughts about
who you might marry?

21:30.040 --> 21:31.040
(SCOFFS)

21:31.080 --> 21:32.957
I ain't doing that again.
I had two marriages.

21:33.040 --> 21:35.315
It just cost the studio a lot
of money to bust them up.

21:35.400 --> 21:36.674
Well, we had to
have those annulled.

21:36.760 --> 21:38.000
One was to
a minor mob figure...

21:38.080 --> 21:39.798
Vince was not minor.

21:39.960 --> 21:40.949
And Buddy Flynn
was a bandleader

21:41.040 --> 21:42.837
with a long history
of narcotic use.

21:43.000 --> 21:44.797
Yeah, yeah, that's what I'm saying.
They were both louses.

21:44.880 --> 21:46.916
Marrying a third louse
ain't gonna do me no good.

21:47.080 --> 21:49.160
We've offered you some very
suitable, clean young men.

21:49.200 --> 21:50.918
Pretty boys,
saps and swishes!

21:51.000 --> 21:53.195
What, you think if there
wasn't a good, reliable man,

21:53.280 --> 21:54.360
I wouldn't have
grabbed him?

21:54.440 --> 21:56.556
What about Arne Seslum?
He is the father, isn't he?

21:56.760 --> 21:57.909
Yeah, yeah.

21:58.000 --> 21:59.877
The marriage doesn't
have to last forever.

22:00.040 --> 22:01.837
But, DeeAnna,
having a child without a father

22:02.000 --> 22:04.200
would present a public-relations
problem for the studio.

22:04.240 --> 22:06.310
The aquatic pictures
do very nicely for us.

22:06.880 --> 22:09.519
So you go and strap on a
fish-ass and marry Arne Seslum.

22:09.720 --> 22:11.233
The pictures do well
for all of us,

22:11.320 --> 22:12.799
and it's a tribute to you.

22:12.880 --> 22:15.314
The public loves you because
they know how innocent you are.

22:15.680 --> 22:17.113
That's true.

22:17.200 --> 22:18.679
Let me see if Arne
is open to matrimony.

22:18.760 --> 22:19.880
You're sure he's the father?

22:19.920 --> 22:22.639
Yeah, yeah. Absolutely,
he's the father, yes!

22:23.000 --> 22:24.069
Pretty sure.

22:24.960 --> 22:26.678
Hey, Maxie,
bring me my ass back.

22:27.560 --> 22:29.039
Hey, hey, buddy,
come here!

22:44.320 --> 22:45.435
How you doing, Hobie?

22:45.600 --> 22:46.794
Hello there, Scotty.

22:46.880 --> 22:48.598
They got you
shooting on the lot?

22:48.720 --> 22:51.154
Uh, well, Mr. Mannix
pulled me off the western.

22:51.320 --> 22:53.390
Says I'm doing
a movie on a sound stage.

22:53.480 --> 22:55.675
They built a drawing room.

23:13.400 --> 23:14.958
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

23:20.000 --> 23:22.389
(DOOR CREAKING)

23:30.800 --> 23:31.800
CREW MEMBER: He's here.

23:33.720 --> 23:36.234
Oh, my dear boy.
Welcome.

23:36.560 --> 23:38.198
Laurence Laurentz.

23:38.360 --> 23:41.079
And you look wonderful, wonderful.
How do you feel?

23:41.600 --> 23:44.512
Uh, well, this here
collar is a little tight.

23:44.680 --> 23:46.591
No, no, no.
It's nicely fit, looks a marvel.

23:46.680 --> 23:48.557
Oh.
Just takes a little getting used to.

23:49.400 --> 23:51.755
Now, Hobie,
here is our set.

23:51.920 --> 23:54.559
And, in fact, that's right, yes,
you enter from there,

23:54.720 --> 23:56.995
having just seen
Biff's valise in the foyer,

23:57.200 --> 24:00.749
in spite of Allegra's claim that
he hasn't been to the house.

24:00.960 --> 24:02.916
I'm sweet on Allegra.
Indeed you are.

24:03.080 --> 24:04.354
But I seen
Biff's grip.

24:04.440 --> 24:05.668
Indeed you have.

24:05.880 --> 24:08.110
And so here we
find you, Hobie...

24:08.200 --> 24:10.555
We find you haunted
by unspoken suspicions.

24:10.760 --> 24:12.273
Haunted.
By Biff's grip.

24:12.440 --> 24:14.317
By his
valise, yes.

24:14.480 --> 24:17.711
But here is Dierdre

24:17.800 --> 24:19.791
harboring deep
feelings for you,

24:19.880 --> 24:21.199
and sensing opportunity.

24:21.360 --> 24:22.634
Dierdre.
Dierdre, yes.

24:22.720 --> 24:25.109
So at her importuning,
you join her on the couch

24:25.280 --> 24:27.350
and conversation ensues.

24:28.360 --> 24:29.360
Um...

24:30.760 --> 24:33.194
So, she's gonna
importune, Mr. Laurence?

24:33.360 --> 24:34.429
Laurentz.

24:34.520 --> 24:35.794
Oh, I'm sorry.

24:35.880 --> 24:37.916
She's gonna importune,
Mr. Laurentz?

24:38.000 --> 24:39.718
Is that something
I should be concerned about?

24:39.800 --> 24:41.028
No, she'll simply
ask you to join her

24:41.160 --> 24:42.354
on the couch,
is all I mean to say,

24:42.440 --> 24:43.429
and then conversation ensues.

24:43.520 --> 24:44.520
Okay. Okay.
I gotcha.

24:44.640 --> 24:46.437
Very good, very good.
Let's try one, shall we? (CLEARS THROAT)

24:46.520 --> 24:47.953
Sure. (CHUCKLES)
I'll give it a go.

24:48.120 --> 24:49.712
Wonderful, splendid.

24:49.920 --> 24:52.150
Now, the only thing
I would suggest is,

24:53.600 --> 24:56.353
before your first line,
you respond to her line

24:56.440 --> 24:59.477
with a
mirthless chuckle.

25:00.960 --> 25:02.109
A mirthless chuckle.

25:02.280 --> 25:03.960
Yes, I think given your
unspoken suspicions

25:04.040 --> 25:05.553
about Allegra,

25:06.120 --> 25:07.553
a mirthless chuckle.

25:07.640 --> 25:09.756
Uh-huh. Okay, Mr. Laurence,
I'll give it a shot.

25:09.920 --> 25:10.989
Laurentz.

25:11.080 --> 25:13.469
Oh, gosh, I'm so sorry,
Mr. Laurentz.

25:13.560 --> 25:14.675
I'll give it a shot.

25:22.640 --> 25:23.834
(DOOR RATTLES)

25:23.920 --> 25:24.989
(BELL RINGING)

25:25.080 --> 25:27.040
CLAPPER BOY: Merrily We Dance.
27-apple, take one.

25:30.080 --> 25:31.308
LAURENCE: Action.

25:32.160 --> 25:34.037
(RATTLING)

25:36.560 --> 25:37.560
DIERDRE: Oh, Monty.

25:38.200 --> 25:39.872
Come join me
on the divan.

25:50.600 --> 25:51.794
(FOOT THUMPS)

25:58.040 --> 25:59.553
It seems
Allegra's a no-show,

25:59.640 --> 26:01.312
which is simply a bore.

26:01.480 --> 26:03.391
But I'll partner
you in bridge.

26:04.480 --> 26:05.993
Why the pout?

26:06.480 --> 26:07.480
Ha!

26:08.040 --> 26:10.156
Would that it were so simple.

26:16.480 --> 26:17.549
Uh, cut.

26:18.160 --> 26:20.280
(BELL RINGING)
CREW MEMBER: That's a cut. Back to one.

26:21.360 --> 26:24.238
Very good.
Wonderful, in fact.

26:26.040 --> 26:27.917
But, um, let's try it
a little differently this time.

26:28.000 --> 26:29.149
Sure.
Let's try...

26:30.200 --> 26:31.952
Let's see, first of all,
why don't we

26:32.040 --> 26:33.758
dispense with
the mirthless chuckle?

26:33.920 --> 26:35.353
No mirthless chuckle.

26:35.680 --> 26:38.672
No, no need, really. It was a bad idea.
It was bad directorial.

26:38.840 --> 26:40.432
My fault
overthinking the thing.

26:40.600 --> 26:42.477
If you say so,
but I'm happy to do another,

26:42.560 --> 26:43.754
maybe try her
one more time.

26:43.920 --> 26:46.400
I mean, if you want that chuckle,
I sure wanna give her to you.

26:46.520 --> 26:48.476
No, no, no. Completely unnecessary
under the circumstances.

26:48.560 --> 26:50.073
I think the audience can,
to that extent,

26:50.160 --> 26:51.240
they can read
your thoughts,

26:51.320 --> 26:53.675
and they will assume
your mirthlessness.

26:53.880 --> 26:55.440
Okay, you're the boss man,
Mr. Laurence.

26:55.520 --> 26:56.555
Laurentz.

26:56.760 --> 26:59.593
Oh, gosh.
I am so sorry, Mr. Laurentz.

26:59.800 --> 27:01.518
Also, this time,
let's try actually

27:01.640 --> 27:03.596
looking at Dierdre
as we speak.

27:03.760 --> 27:05.637
Looking into her eyes
and speaking our line

27:05.720 --> 27:07.597
with a certain
ruefulness.

27:08.960 --> 27:10.279
Ruefulness, okay.

27:10.480 --> 27:12.596
Yes. Because it's
not so simple, you see.

27:12.760 --> 27:14.557
Not so simple
as she suggests.

27:14.720 --> 27:15.869
Okay.

27:16.640 --> 27:19.108
Your feelings
are not so simple.

27:19.320 --> 27:20.992
No, sir. Okay.

27:22.480 --> 27:23.515
(BELL RINGING)
CREW MEMBER: Roll camera.

27:23.680 --> 27:25.511
Merrily We Dance.
27-apple, take two.

27:31.560 --> 27:33.391
(SIGHS) Action.

27:37.920 --> 27:38.989
DIERDRE: Oh, Monty.

27:39.280 --> 27:41.510
Come join me
on the divan.

27:50.400 --> 27:53.392
Seems Allegra's a no-show,
which is simply a bore.

27:53.560 --> 27:55.437
But I'll partner
you in bridge.

27:55.600 --> 27:56.999
Why the pout?

27:59.600 --> 28:03.388
(SLOWLY) Would that
it were so simple.

28:07.400 --> 28:08.469
Cut.

28:08.760 --> 28:09.760
(BELL RINGING)

28:13.160 --> 28:14.912
Very good,
very good.

28:15.600 --> 28:17.591
Um... (CLICKS TONGUE)

28:20.640 --> 28:21.709
Come, come.

28:23.400 --> 28:24.628
HOBIE: All right.

28:25.120 --> 28:26.120
(EXHALES)

28:27.520 --> 28:29.192
All right,
let's try this.

28:29.600 --> 28:32.398
Your line, just say it
as I say it.

28:32.600 --> 28:34.591
Say your line exactly
as I'm about to.

28:34.760 --> 28:36.034
Just as
I'm about to do.

28:36.200 --> 28:37.553
Sure, okay.

28:39.480 --> 28:41.118
Would that it
were so simple.

28:41.840 --> 28:42.840
Um...

28:43.120 --> 28:44.678
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

28:44.840 --> 28:46.193
Would that it
were so simple.

28:46.360 --> 28:48.157
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

28:48.320 --> 28:49.355
My dear boy,
why do you say that?

28:49.440 --> 28:50.668
Why do you say "twuuuuuuh"?

28:51.160 --> 28:53.071
You said, "Say it like I said it."
Yes.

28:53.240 --> 28:55.196
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

28:55.360 --> 28:56.480
Would that it
were so simple.

28:56.520 --> 28:58.272
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

28:58.440 --> 29:00.112
Would that it...
Would that ih twuuuuuuh so simple?

29:00.280 --> 29:02.360
No, no, watch my mouth.
Would that it were so simple.

29:02.400 --> 29:03.469
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

29:03.640 --> 29:05.232
Keep your head still.
Would that it were so simple.

29:05.400 --> 29:06.515
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

29:06.720 --> 29:07.869
Would that it
were so simple.

29:08.040 --> 29:09.792
I'm trying to
say that, Mr. Laurentz.

29:09.880 --> 29:10.915
Laurence. Mmm.

29:12.280 --> 29:13.280
I thought...

29:13.960 --> 29:15.712
A minute ago
it was Laurentz.

29:15.880 --> 29:17.472
No, we can use Christian names,
my good dear boy.

29:17.640 --> 29:19.320
Laurence is fine,
just as I call you Hobie.

29:19.400 --> 29:20.435
Okay.

29:20.520 --> 29:22.158
So, would that
it were so simple.

29:22.320 --> 29:23.440
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so...

29:23.600 --> 29:25.750
Keep your hand down, now!
Would that it were so simple. Trippingly.

29:25.920 --> 29:27.720
Would that ih twuuuuuuh
so simple. Trippingly.

29:27.880 --> 29:29.518
No, don't say "trippingly,"
say the line trippingly.

29:29.680 --> 29:31.352
Would that ih twuuuuuuh...
Would that it... (CLEARS THROAT)

29:31.440 --> 29:32.429
Would that it
were so simple.

29:32.520 --> 29:33.509
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

29:33.600 --> 29:34.589
Would that it
were so simple.

29:34.680 --> 29:35.669
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

29:35.760 --> 29:36.749
Would that it
were so simple.

29:36.840 --> 29:37.875
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

29:37.960 --> 29:38.915
Would that it
were so simple.

29:39.040 --> 29:40.951
Would that ih twuuuuuuh so simple.
Rueful, rueful, rueful.

29:41.040 --> 29:42.268
Would that ih twuuuuuuh so simple.
Rueful.

29:42.360 --> 29:43.509
Would that it
were so simple.

29:43.640 --> 29:44.868
Rueful "simple."
Would that ih twuuuuuuh...

29:45.000 --> 29:46.479
Soulful "simple."
Would that ih twuuuuuuh so simple.

29:46.680 --> 29:48.159
Or soulful.
You could say soulful.

29:48.320 --> 29:49.958
Rueful, soulful.
Would that it were so simple.

29:50.120 --> 29:51.553
Would that ih
twuuuuuuh so simple.

29:51.720 --> 29:52.709
What are you
doing this for?

29:52.800 --> 29:53.920
Would that
ih twuuuuuuh so...

29:53.960 --> 29:55.837
Your hands!
Just keep still!

30:08.040 --> 30:10.110
(KNOCK ON THE DOOR)
(DOG BARKING)

30:21.720 --> 30:23.438
PRODUCER: Stall?
For how long?

30:23.520 --> 30:24.475
What do I
tell the director?

30:24.560 --> 30:25.549
EDDIE: That we're
looking for him.

30:25.760 --> 30:27.034
But we don't want it
in the gossip columns.

30:27.200 --> 30:28.599
Baird on a bender,
in a love nest,

30:28.720 --> 30:30.040
or wherever we
end up finding him.

30:30.200 --> 30:32.634
And as far as the set is concerned,
it's business as usual.

30:32.800 --> 30:35.712
Tell the ADs Baird is out briefly
with a high ankle sprain.

30:35.880 --> 30:37.400
Fine, but what do
we shoot without him?

30:37.480 --> 30:39.160
We got the brazier
scene up this afternoon.

30:39.320 --> 30:40.753
Could you get through it
shooting around him?

30:40.840 --> 30:42.520
Maybe use his stunt double,
Chunk Mulligan?

30:43.040 --> 30:44.314
Chunk can't act.

30:44.480 --> 30:46.038
Get the writer to
trim his speeches.

30:46.240 --> 30:47.355
Well, maybe,
but then what do we do?

30:47.440 --> 30:48.919
All we got left
is the final scene.

30:49.000 --> 30:51.514
Autolochus' speech
at the feet of the penitent thief.

30:51.800 --> 30:54.394
It's the emotional climax
of the entire picture.

30:54.480 --> 30:57.950
We gotta see Autolochus has
absorbed the message of the Christ.

30:58.120 --> 30:59.189
Yeah, I can see that.

30:59.280 --> 31:01.032
We need Baird's
star power, his charisma.

31:01.120 --> 31:02.394
Sure, his emotional, uh...

31:02.560 --> 31:04.391
This can't be faked!
It's the heart and soul of the picture.

31:04.560 --> 31:06.516
I understand.
End of the film!

31:06.840 --> 31:09.354
We can't just give
the speech to some...

31:09.600 --> 31:10.999
Some

31:11.080 --> 31:12.433
Roman schmo!

31:12.640 --> 31:14.000
No, no. Yeah, yeah,
yeah, I got it.

31:14.080 --> 31:16.196
But his benders can
last a day or two.

31:17.000 --> 31:18.513
What does it cost
to shut down?

31:18.680 --> 31:20.280
Plenty. You know how
big this picture is?

31:20.320 --> 31:22.151
We're on Stages 5 and 14.

31:22.320 --> 31:24.515
If we're carrying everybody
in the final scene

31:24.600 --> 31:25.953
who's up on crucifixes

31:26.120 --> 31:29.237
that's $3.40 an hour hardship pay,
eight hour minimum.

31:29.400 --> 31:30.549
Yeah.
Plus we lose...

31:30.640 --> 31:32.073
NATALIE: (ON INTERCOM)
Mr. Mannix, I'm sorry... Not now.

31:32.200 --> 31:34.634
We lose Todd Hocheiser to Fox
at the end of the week.

31:34.720 --> 31:35.709
We should have
made him exclusive.

31:35.800 --> 31:36.800
Who knew?
(PHONE BUZZES)

31:36.840 --> 31:38.120
NATALIE: I'm sorry, sir.
Not now!

31:38.160 --> 31:40.879
It's Mr. Laurentz.
I can't stop him!

31:41.280 --> 31:42.918
Mannix, I won't have it!
NATALIE: No! No!

31:43.000 --> 31:45.309
For two decades the words
"Laurence Laurentz Presents"

31:45.400 --> 31:46.469
have meant something
to the public.

31:46.720 --> 31:48.676
It's all right, Natalie.
Okay, Walt, let me know.

31:49.120 --> 31:50.120
(SIGHS)

31:50.200 --> 31:52.350
What's on your
mind, Laurence?

31:52.520 --> 31:54.476
Hobie Doyle cannot act!

31:55.000 --> 31:56.558
Hobart Doyle is
one of the biggest

31:56.640 --> 31:57.993
movie stars in the world.

31:58.160 --> 31:59.229
On horseback.

31:59.320 --> 32:00.992
But this is a drama,
Mannix, a real drama.

32:01.160 --> 32:02.912
It's an adaptation
of a Broadway smash!

32:03.080 --> 32:05.275
It requires the skills
of a trained thespian,

32:05.480 --> 32:07.198
not a rodeo clown!

32:07.400 --> 32:08.628
I begged you for Lunt!

32:08.800 --> 32:10.677
Mr. Mannix, I'm sorry,
but you wanted me to make sure

32:10.760 --> 32:12.910
you didn't miss your lunch
at the Imperial Gardens.

32:13.080 --> 32:14.354
You never told me who with.

32:14.520 --> 32:15.589
Nuts.

32:15.680 --> 32:17.636
Look, no one
wants to see Lunt.

32:17.720 --> 32:20.075
We're not recasting.
This came from Mr. Schenk himself.

32:20.160 --> 32:22.196
It's Hobie Doyle.
Is the boy game?

32:22.360 --> 32:24.590
No, he's game.
And gamey!

32:24.760 --> 32:26.720
Well, if he needs help,
it's your job to help him.

32:26.840 --> 32:29.115
I'll have a talk with Hobie and
take a look at what you've shot,

32:29.280 --> 32:31.157
but right now
I've got a lunch.

32:39.680 --> 32:43.992
"Truth to these
mutterings, Sestimus."

32:44.160 --> 32:45.752
(GROANING)

32:46.720 --> 32:47.720
(MUMBLING)

32:50.720 --> 32:51.720
(DOORBELL RINGS)

32:52.280 --> 32:53.280
(DOG BARKING)

32:54.040 --> 32:56.031
(INDISTINCT)

33:08.240 --> 33:09.468
Quiet, Engels!

33:16.000 --> 33:17.911
How pleasant to
see you, Mr. Mannix.

33:18.000 --> 33:19.718
Your table is
right over here.

33:19.880 --> 33:21.279
Thank you, Arthur.

33:24.600 --> 33:25.953
How you doing, Mannix?

33:26.120 --> 33:27.439
Mr. Cuddahy.

33:27.600 --> 33:30.319
They mix a hell of a Mai Tai.
I like this place.

33:30.480 --> 33:33.631
Sorry to keep you hanging.
It's a tough decision.

33:33.800 --> 33:37.395
Nothing to apologize for. We said the
deal was on the table for a week.

33:37.920 --> 33:38.920
Oh.

33:39.480 --> 33:40.629
Go ahead.

33:41.840 --> 33:43.671
No, I'm
trying to quit.

33:44.400 --> 33:45.674
I just wanted
to visit again

33:45.760 --> 33:47.591
to see if there was some
impediment we could help with,

33:47.760 --> 33:49.273
or if something in
the offer isn't clear?

33:49.360 --> 33:51.396
No, the offer's very clear.
And very generous.

33:51.560 --> 33:53.755
We want to make it easy
for you to say yes.

33:55.480 --> 33:57.072
Mannix, we need a guy with
your talents in management,

33:57.160 --> 33:58.673
problem-solving.

33:58.840 --> 34:00.876
And you need to
think about the future.

34:01.040 --> 34:02.758
Lockheed is booming.

34:02.920 --> 34:04.120
Everyone's
riding in airplanes,

34:04.200 --> 34:06.111
and we're moving
into jet airplanes.

34:06.280 --> 34:08.668
It's a new age, Mannix,
and we're part of it.

34:08.840 --> 34:11.797
The industry you're in,
what's the future there?

34:12.000 --> 34:14.116
What happens when everybody
owns a television set?

34:14.199 --> 34:16.110
Will they still be going
to pictures every week?

34:16.320 --> 34:17.840
Well, we like to
think that families...

34:17.960 --> 34:19.154
I don't mean to denigrate.

34:19.239 --> 34:21.833
I'm sure the picture business
is pretty damned interesting.

34:22.000 --> 34:25.072
But it's also pretty
frivolous, isn't it?

34:25.440 --> 34:29.319
Aviation is serious.
Serious business, serious people.

34:29.480 --> 34:32.358
You won't be babysitting a
lot of oddballs and misfits,

34:32.520 --> 34:34.280
shouldering a lot of
crackpot problems for...

34:34.320 --> 34:36.038
We have some
kooks, sure, but...

34:36.199 --> 34:38.839
(CHUCKLES) Of course they're kooks!
It's all make-believe.

34:41.000 --> 34:42.000
(CHUCKLES)

34:42.080 --> 34:43.228
I told myself
I wasn't gonna

34:43.320 --> 34:45.150
badmouth the competition,
and look at me.

34:45.320 --> 34:47.788
Sorry, Mannix.
I'll stick with what we're about.

34:47.960 --> 34:49.188
Let me show
you something.

34:49.840 --> 34:51.751
Ever heard of
the Bikini Atoll?

34:51.920 --> 34:52.955
No.

34:53.800 --> 34:54.835
Test site.

34:55.000 --> 34:56.478
Just couple of rocks in the
middle of the Pacific,

34:56.560 --> 34:58.312
until a few weeks ago,

34:58.480 --> 35:00.198
when we blew
the H-erino.

35:00.760 --> 35:02.273
I shouldn't be
telling you this.

35:03.480 --> 35:05.072
It's the real world.

35:05.280 --> 35:06.508
Hydrogen bomb.

35:07.480 --> 35:08.879
Fusion device.

35:10.480 --> 35:11.708
Armageddon.

35:11.800 --> 35:13.840
And Lockheed was there.
We had a... (BEADS JANGLING)

35:13.880 --> 35:15.199
Call for you,
Mr. Mannix.

35:15.880 --> 35:16.880
Oh, thank you.

35:19.120 --> 35:20.235
Hello?

35:22.280 --> 35:23.599
Yeah, he has it now?

35:24.520 --> 35:26.750
No, have him stay on set,
I'll go to him.

35:28.360 --> 35:30.510
Sorry, Cuddahy,
work emergency.

35:30.600 --> 35:32.750
Still do work there,
for the day anyway.

35:32.920 --> 35:35.309
You make a good case.
I'll let you know.

35:38.520 --> 35:39.520
(DEVICE WHIRRING)
(THUD)

35:41.200 --> 35:42.200
(THUDDING CONTINUES)

35:56.920 --> 35:57.920
(GRUNTS)

36:25.560 --> 36:26.560
(THUD)

36:42.560 --> 36:43.560
(VACUUM CLEANER STOPS)

36:43.800 --> 36:44.800
Uh...

36:44.880 --> 36:46.393
You one of the
Hollywood people?

36:49.800 --> 36:51.119
Maybe.

36:51.640 --> 36:52.868
They're in there.

36:53.880 --> 36:54.880
(VACUUM CLEANER STARTS)

37:04.600 --> 37:06.750
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

37:11.400 --> 37:13.277
(CHATTER GROWS LOUDER)

37:13.520 --> 37:14.520
(DOOR CREAKING)

37:22.480 --> 37:26.553
Please, enter.
All are welcome.

37:44.480 --> 37:45.480
(GRUNTS)

37:50.640 --> 37:51.914
Those things
are a nuisance.

37:54.120 --> 37:55.189
Thank you.

37:58.520 --> 38:00.670
We'll have sandwiches
in a minute.

38:01.520 --> 38:03.636
Tea?

38:05.280 --> 38:07.157
Uh, okay.

38:07.320 --> 38:09.197
Yeah. (CLEARS THROAT)
And, uh...

38:09.360 --> 38:11.669
And what's going on?

38:11.760 --> 38:12.875
Yeah.

38:13.040 --> 38:14.712
Well, we've just
read the minutes.

38:14.880 --> 38:16.871
And Alan was about to
bring up new business.

38:20.720 --> 38:22.711
Well, I missed
the minutes.

38:23.200 --> 38:24.394
I wouldn't
worry about it.

38:24.560 --> 38:26.630
They're usually
pretty boring.

38:32.880 --> 38:34.677
What kind of
a meeting is this?

38:34.840 --> 38:36.319
HEAD WRITER: Well,
it's not a meeting

38:36.480 --> 38:37.993
so much as a...

38:38.680 --> 38:42.912
It's, uh, more of
a study group.

38:43.080 --> 38:44.513
And you're studying?

38:45.000 --> 38:46.399
All sorts of jolly stuff.

38:46.560 --> 38:48.152
History.
Economics.

38:48.320 --> 38:49.753
WRITER 1: Same thing,
isn't it?

38:49.920 --> 38:52.150
History, economics.

38:52.320 --> 38:53.753
Don't you agree?

38:56.920 --> 39:01.198
I'm not really
a student of history.

39:05.480 --> 39:06.480
(DOG BARKING)

39:06.720 --> 39:07.720
WRITER 2: Quiet, Engels!

39:08.520 --> 39:09.520
BAIRD: Thank you.

39:09.880 --> 39:11.757
Man is split?

39:11.920 --> 39:13.433
Well, Man's functions
are split.

39:13.600 --> 39:17.149
There's the little guy, the regular
Joe who works for a living.

39:17.240 --> 39:19.549
He's the body,
body politic.

39:19.720 --> 39:22.075
Then there's the brain,
the boss, the owner.

39:22.240 --> 39:23.559
The boss is
not the brain.

39:23.720 --> 39:25.233
No, no!
The boss is parasite!

39:25.680 --> 39:29.116
HEAD WRITER: Well, it's true that the
boss doesn't work, but he has a function.

39:29.280 --> 39:30.599
He controls the means of...

39:30.800 --> 39:33.598
Production. Sure,
but that's not a function, that's...

39:33.760 --> 39:35.796
Parasitism!
On the... Shut up!

39:35.960 --> 39:38.793
On the body politic. Of the regular Joe!
WRITER 3: Shut up!

39:39.840 --> 39:40.840
(CLEARS THROAT)

39:45.480 --> 39:48.313
Man is unitary.

39:48.480 --> 39:50.869
A simple economic agent.

39:51.040 --> 39:53.474
Man's institutions
are split,

39:53.640 --> 39:57.155
expressing contradictions
that must be worked through.

39:57.560 --> 40:03.237
And they are worked through in
a causative, predictable way.

40:04.320 --> 40:06.151
History is science.

40:06.640 --> 40:09.632
This is the essence of the dialectic.
(WRITERS AGREEING)

40:10.480 --> 40:12.277
You see, if you
understand economics,

40:12.480 --> 40:15.233
you can actually write down
what will happen in the future.

40:15.400 --> 40:18.233
With as much confidence as you write
down the history of the past.

40:18.320 --> 40:21.756
Because it's science.
It's not make believe.

40:21.920 --> 40:23.831
We don't believe
in Santa Claus.

40:23.960 --> 40:24.960
(ALL LAUGHING)

40:25.240 --> 40:26.593
Another finger sandwich?

40:26.760 --> 40:29.479
Thank you. Now if I follow this
correctly... (CAMERA CLICKS)

40:30.680 --> 40:31.680
Who's that guy?

40:33.280 --> 40:37.114
Uh, Mr. Smitrovich takes
pictures for our newsletter.

40:38.120 --> 40:41.317
Our understanding of the
true workings of history

40:41.480 --> 40:44.233
gives us access to
the levers of power.

40:44.320 --> 40:48.950
Your studio, for instance,
is a pure instrument of capitalism.

40:49.120 --> 40:53.875
As such, it expresses the
contradictions of capitalism

40:54.040 --> 40:59.717
and can be enlisted to
finance its own destruction.

41:00.200 --> 41:01.428
Which is exciting.

41:01.640 --> 41:04.871
It can be made to help the
little guy, the regular Joe.

41:05.040 --> 41:06.553
The body politic!
Shut up!

41:06.720 --> 41:09.188
Even though its purpose
is to exploit the little guy.

41:09.400 --> 41:10.719
WRITER 4: And
the body politic.

41:10.880 --> 41:12.520
You're for the little guy?
(CAMERA CLICKS)

41:12.600 --> 41:14.318
For the little guy or against,
it doesn't matter.

41:14.400 --> 41:15.913
History will be
what it will be,

41:16.000 --> 41:17.035
and we already
know what it'll be.

41:17.240 --> 41:18.673
But yes, we're
for the little guy.

41:18.840 --> 41:20.558
Aren't you?
Shut up!

41:20.720 --> 41:23.188
Are you joking?
Me, for the little guy?

41:23.280 --> 41:24.560
Of course I'm for
the little guy.

41:24.680 --> 41:26.238
What, is this guy
a comedian?

41:26.520 --> 41:27.520
(ALL CHUCKLING)

41:30.080 --> 41:33.390
Listen, I better get back.
The studio's gotta be going nuts.

41:33.480 --> 41:35.152
Can we cut it off now and
pick it up right here

41:35.240 --> 41:37.435
at the next
study session?

41:37.560 --> 41:38.595
(CLEARS THROAT)

41:39.600 --> 41:43.070
Okay, well, see...

41:45.560 --> 41:47.676
I'm afraid it's
not that simple.

41:50.440 --> 41:56.436
NARRATOR: And so, Baird Whitlock found
himself in the hands of communists.

41:56.600 --> 42:00.434
Meanwhile, far from
the crashing surf of Malibu,

42:00.600 --> 42:04.593
Eddie Mannix, torn from his lunch
with a Lockheed man,

42:04.760 --> 42:07.832
hurries back to the vastness
of Capitol Pictures,

42:08.040 --> 42:10.600
whose tireless
machinery clanks on,

42:10.760 --> 42:13.354
producing this year's
ration of dreams

42:13.480 --> 42:16.119
for all the weary
peoples of the world.

42:16.280 --> 42:19.078
Hey, numbskull. Didn't you
see the rolling light was on?

42:19.240 --> 42:21.800
Oh, I'm sorry, Mr. Mannix.
Can I help you find someone?

42:21.960 --> 42:23.109
No.

42:23.200 --> 42:24.792
URSULINA: Autolochus!
AUTOLOCHUS: Yes?

42:25.560 --> 42:28.916
Why do you present yourself in my
chambers in such humble fashion?

42:29.080 --> 42:31.275
Do not look
upon me, Ursulina.

42:31.480 --> 42:33.357
The fires of the
brazier of Sestimus

42:33.440 --> 42:35.476
have latterly
burned my face!

42:35.640 --> 42:36.920
Though the unguents
of Arkimideus

42:37.000 --> 42:39.150
promise shortly
to undo the damage.

42:39.320 --> 42:42.392
Autolochus, you know
that my love is for you,

42:42.480 --> 42:43.549
not for your station.

42:44.480 --> 42:50.157
AUTOLOCHUS: And my ardor for you...
(STAMMERING)

42:50.240 --> 42:52.117
CHUNK: I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

42:55.920 --> 42:57.478
"We are the Future."

42:58.400 --> 42:59.549
What does
that mean?

42:59.760 --> 43:00.909
Beats me.

43:01.640 --> 43:02.920
Somebody slipped
it under my door

43:03.000 --> 43:04.672
sometime after we
broke this morning.

43:04.840 --> 43:06.068
Mention it
to anyone?

43:06.160 --> 43:07.229
Nope.

43:07.320 --> 43:09.151
Okay, well, let's
keep it that way.

43:11.520 --> 43:14.751
Hey, by the way,
Chunk sounded good in there.

43:17.080 --> 43:19.514
Natalie, could you please get
me Stu Schwartz, Accounting?

43:20.680 --> 43:22.830
(LINE BUZZES)
NATALIE: Stu Schwartz on two.

43:23.840 --> 43:26.638
Stu, how are ya?
I need some petty cash.

43:26.800 --> 43:28.199
$100,000.

43:28.360 --> 43:29.839
I'm sorry,
did I say petty?

43:30.040 --> 43:31.837
Well, it's a long story,
and I'll tell it to you some time.

43:32.040 --> 43:33.678
You have that much
in the office?

43:33.880 --> 43:35.950
Yeah, how much space
will that take up?

43:36.200 --> 43:37.235
Uh, Mr. Mannix?

43:37.320 --> 43:38.514
All right,
this might do it.

43:39.360 --> 43:41.032
Uh, Thora Thacker
just came in.

43:41.200 --> 43:42.519
Wonders if you
have a moment.

43:43.520 --> 43:45.636
Thora Thacker.

43:45.720 --> 43:47.199
Tell her I'm
stuck on a call.

43:47.440 --> 43:48.998
I'll leave
through the patio.

43:51.200 --> 43:53.077
Call didn't take
so long then.

43:53.160 --> 43:55.151
Yes. No.
Fast talkers.

43:55.360 --> 43:56.554
What can I
do for you, Thora?

43:56.720 --> 43:57.948
Well, I'll be
fast, too.

43:58.040 --> 43:59.837
I only wanted to
notify you as a courtesy

43:59.920 --> 44:02.229
that I am running my
Baird Whitlock story.

44:02.400 --> 44:03.628
Yeah?
What's the story?

44:03.720 --> 44:07.076
The story. I have a credible
source and I am going to run it,

44:07.240 --> 44:08.798
and I think you know
what story I mean.

44:09.000 --> 44:10.115
I have no idea.

44:10.200 --> 44:12.111
There's nothing going on with Baird.
I would know, wouldn't I?

44:12.200 --> 44:13.428
Don't play dumb, Eddie.

44:13.520 --> 44:14.794
I am talking about

44:15.840 --> 44:18.070
On Wings as Eagles.

44:20.040 --> 44:21.109
What?

44:21.200 --> 44:22.349
Running it tomorrow.

44:23.160 --> 44:24.388
First of all...

44:25.720 --> 44:27.597
First of all, there's
nothing to that story.

44:27.680 --> 44:28.908
I've heard it,
it's been around forever,

44:29.000 --> 44:30.228
and it's never
been confirmed.

44:30.320 --> 44:31.753
And secondly,
you can't print that.

44:31.920 --> 44:33.353
Even if you could print it,
you couldn't print it.

44:33.560 --> 44:34.993
And you wouldn't want to, Thora.
It's beneath you.

44:35.160 --> 44:36.513
The facts are
never beneath me.

44:36.680 --> 44:38.910
People don't want the facts,
they wanna believe!

44:39.080 --> 44:41.674
That's our great industry,
mine and yours, too.

44:41.760 --> 44:42.954
They wanna believe
that Baird Whitlock

44:43.040 --> 44:44.758
is a great star
and a good man.

44:44.920 --> 44:45.989
You're admitting he isn't.

44:46.120 --> 44:48.190
No, I'm saying he is,
though it's beside the point.

44:48.360 --> 44:50.237
There's nothing to it,
nothing to the gossip.

44:50.400 --> 44:52.516
I am not
a gossip columnist!

44:52.680 --> 44:53.795
No, no, no,
of course not.

44:53.920 --> 44:55.717
Don't confuse me
with my sister!

44:55.920 --> 44:58.275
Hardly. But look, do you
have to run it tomorrow?

44:58.680 --> 44:59.999
It's my entire column.

45:00.080 --> 45:01.600
I'm happy to talk
to Baird for comment,

45:01.640 --> 45:03.120
but it will have to
be this afternoon.

45:03.280 --> 45:04.793
Baird's unavailable
right now. Wait one day.

45:04.880 --> 45:05.880
Ha!

45:05.960 --> 45:07.473
Thora, wait one
day and I'll give you

45:07.600 --> 45:09.272
a true story for
tomorrow's column.

45:09.360 --> 45:11.271
A little something

45:11.400 --> 45:12.799
about Hobie Doyle.

45:12.960 --> 45:14.313
My readers don't
care about Hobie Doyle.

45:14.440 --> 45:15.475
He wears chaps!

45:15.640 --> 45:16.789
Do they care about
Carlotta Valdez?

45:16.880 --> 45:18.000
They're sweet on each other.

45:18.040 --> 45:20.400
You should see the two of them together.
Like peas in a pod.

45:20.920 --> 45:23.036
Trade the story of my career for
a puff piece on Hobie Doyle?

45:23.120 --> 45:24.553
I don't think so.

45:24.640 --> 45:26.073
You're not trading anything,
you're waiting one day

45:26.200 --> 45:27.599
on a story
that's years old.

45:27.680 --> 45:29.432
Wait one day.
I can let you talk to Baird,

45:29.520 --> 45:30.589
show you your
story's the bunk.

45:30.680 --> 45:33.148
If I'm wrong, no skin off your nose.
You run the column.

45:33.240 --> 45:34.760
In the meantime,
you have an exclusive.

45:34.960 --> 45:36.951
No one else knows
about Hobie and Carlotta.

45:37.120 --> 45:38.838
No kidding.
You're it.

45:39.720 --> 45:41.233
What kind of name
is Thora, anyway?

45:41.320 --> 45:43.754
It's a name that 19
million readers trust.

45:43.920 --> 45:45.478
Don't play games
with them, Eddie.

45:45.680 --> 45:47.557
Oh, nobody's
playing games here.

45:50.280 --> 45:51.280
(BAG STRAINING)

45:51.480 --> 45:52.833
Is that big enough?

45:53.080 --> 45:54.080
(LOCKS LATCHING)

45:56.160 --> 45:58.310
Hello, Eddie.
I'm notifying you as a courtesy

45:58.440 --> 46:00.237
before I run
tomorrow's story.

46:00.440 --> 46:02.510
Thessaly? Yeah,
I just saw your...

46:02.680 --> 46:04.671
Ah, never mind. How you doing?
What's the story?

46:04.840 --> 46:06.193
It's about
Baird Whitlock.

46:06.280 --> 46:08.561
There's absolutely no truth to
that old story, believe me.

46:08.640 --> 46:09.834
Old?
Old, stale, rotten and...

46:09.920 --> 46:11.831
I'm talking about today.

46:11.920 --> 46:13.239
What?

46:13.320 --> 46:15.959
A little bird told me that he
disappeared from the set today.

46:16.040 --> 46:17.598
Oh, that! No, no.

46:17.760 --> 46:19.273
Yes, he did
have to take a break.

46:19.360 --> 46:20.839
Minor injury.
High ankle sprain.

46:21.000 --> 46:22.069
What did you
think I meant?

46:22.160 --> 46:23.878
No, nothing. I saw
your sister earlier.

46:24.040 --> 46:25.871
She was trying to resurrect
some old gossip about Baird.

46:26.040 --> 46:28.110
Oh, I'm sure
she was, that cow!

46:28.200 --> 46:30.640
She wouldn't know a news story
if it bit her on the posterior.

46:30.680 --> 46:32.200
Yeah, well, she's...
High ankle sprain?

46:32.280 --> 46:34.120
Is that really the best
you could come up with?

46:34.200 --> 46:36.953
We all know about the womanizing
and the drinking jags

46:37.120 --> 46:38.473
and those trips
to San Berdoo.

46:38.560 --> 46:39.629
Baird is a
good family man.

46:39.800 --> 46:41.870
He has a high ankle sprain.

46:42.040 --> 46:43.314
Mr. Mannix?

46:43.480 --> 46:44.549
What's up, Peanut?

46:44.640 --> 46:46.710
Natalie told me
to find you PDQ.

46:46.880 --> 46:48.029
I know it sounds screwy,
but she said

46:48.120 --> 46:49.553
someone's calling
from the future.

46:50.240 --> 46:52.629
Good Lord! Thessaly,
I have to run.

46:52.720 --> 46:55.234
If you do know where Baird is,
you must let me talk to him.

46:55.400 --> 46:57.311
Sure. I'll find out where
he is right away, Thessaly,

46:57.400 --> 46:58.515
and I'm sure...

46:58.680 --> 47:00.398
Say, what kind of
name is Thessaly, anyway?

47:00.560 --> 47:02.551
It's a name that 20
million readers trust.

47:02.720 --> 47:04.233
They want the truth, Eddie.

47:04.400 --> 47:06.516
The truth, yes.
Mmm-hmm.

47:07.240 --> 47:09.276
We're gonna
give it to them.

47:10.760 --> 47:13.149
On three.
And Hobie Doyle is in there.

47:13.320 --> 47:14.992
Hey.
HOBIE: Hello, Mr. Mannix.

47:15.160 --> 47:17.390
EDDIE: Thanks for
coming, Hobie. One second.

47:19.000 --> 47:20.080
Hello, Mannix...
(DIAL TONE)

47:20.720 --> 47:22.073
Damn.

47:22.400 --> 47:24.072
Hung up, Natalie.
Tell me the second they call back.

47:24.440 --> 47:25.589
NATALIE: Yes, sir.

47:25.760 --> 47:26.988
What's going
on there, Mr. Mannix?

47:27.080 --> 47:28.991
Looks like you're
expecting rain.

47:29.200 --> 47:30.758
No, it's nothing.

47:30.920 --> 47:32.433
How's the first
day on the picture?

47:32.520 --> 47:34.112
You getting comfortable?

47:34.760 --> 47:36.120
Oh, I guess it's
going pretty good.

47:36.240 --> 47:39.198
Uh, that Mr. Laurentz,
he's an awful good man.

47:39.280 --> 47:40.679
He's helping me
get through it.

47:40.840 --> 47:42.398
I give him all the
credit in the world,

47:42.480 --> 47:44.516
me being the new hand
in the bunkhouse.

47:44.680 --> 47:46.511
They got me talking a lot,

47:46.600 --> 47:47.794
which takes a little
getting used to,

47:47.960 --> 47:51.430
talking with the camera looking
at me, but, heck, I enjoy.

47:51.600 --> 47:52.715
Oh, good, that's fine.

47:52.800 --> 47:55.917
Usually on a picture,
I just say, "Whitey" or "Whoa, there."

47:56.080 --> 47:58.275
But this one here,
it's talking.

47:58.360 --> 47:59.793
And it's people listening.

47:59.960 --> 48:01.552
That threw me
a little at first,

48:01.640 --> 48:03.756
but I think I got
my leg up on her now.

48:03.920 --> 48:05.399
That's fine.
Laurentz came by this morning

48:05.480 --> 48:06.760
to tell me how
well you're doing.

48:06.800 --> 48:08.950
You just continue to
do whatever he says.

48:09.040 --> 48:10.598
He knows how to make
a quality picture.

48:11.240 --> 48:13.754
That is true. He will not quit
on a take until it has quality.

48:13.840 --> 48:15.876
(LINE BUZZES)
That them?

48:15.960 --> 48:17.313
NATALIE: Sorry, sir, no.

48:17.400 --> 48:19.550
Do you want
Mrs. Mannix on one?

48:23.480 --> 48:24.629
Hiya, hon.

48:25.480 --> 48:27.118
You know, busy.

48:27.440 --> 48:28.440
Uh-huh.

48:29.520 --> 48:30.520
Uh-huh.

48:32.080 --> 48:34.435
I thought he asked
to play infield.

48:35.840 --> 48:36.955
I see.

48:37.120 --> 48:38.997
Maybe we should make him
honor that commitment.

48:41.520 --> 48:44.080
That's true.
No, of course, you're right.

48:44.240 --> 48:46.470
Okay. Okay,
I'll call the coach.

48:46.640 --> 48:47.834
Sure.

48:48.960 --> 48:50.188
I love you, too.

48:56.360 --> 48:57.395
Mr. Mannix,
you want me to run out

48:57.480 --> 48:58.520
and get you a bigger grip?

48:58.680 --> 49:00.477
That one looks
a little bit snug.

49:00.640 --> 49:01.640
(LOCKS CLICKING)

49:15.720 --> 49:17.119
Hobie.

49:18.040 --> 49:20.793
There's $100,000 in
that attach case.

49:22.560 --> 49:23.879
Ransom money.

49:24.800 --> 49:26.995
Baird Whitlock
has been kidnapped.

49:32.040 --> 49:33.553
This is bad.

49:36.160 --> 49:38.116
Bad for movie stars
everywhere.

49:42.560 --> 49:45.074
And you got no idea who's
mixed up in this thing?

49:49.680 --> 49:51.477
I would look at the extras.

49:51.640 --> 49:53.915
The extras? Why?

49:55.080 --> 49:57.913
Well, you just never know about an extra.
They come and go.

49:58.080 --> 50:00.958
Everyone else, I'm on the set,
I see the guy setting the 5K,

50:01.040 --> 50:03.554
I think, "Why, there's
old Bud setting the 5K."

50:03.720 --> 50:06.029
Script girl,
wrangler, same thing.

50:06.200 --> 50:07.713
Extras, that's different.

50:08.000 --> 50:09.831
Not making
a blanket call here.

50:09.920 --> 50:12.832
I mean, there's good
extras and bad extras.

50:12.920 --> 50:14.751
All I'm saying

50:15.480 --> 50:16.480
(CLEARS THROAT)

50:16.920 --> 50:19.514
you look at an extra,

50:19.600 --> 50:21.909
you got no idea
what he's thinking.

50:22.600 --> 50:23.635
(LINE BUZZES)

50:23.720 --> 50:25.438
NATALIE:
He's back! Line two.

50:26.280 --> 50:27.633
Hello.
You have the money?

50:27.840 --> 50:29.273
Yes, I have it.

50:29.440 --> 50:30.714
Stage 8?

50:30.920 --> 50:33.354
Behind the electrical box?
Just leave it there?

50:33.520 --> 50:35.511
And when do I get Baird?
When we have the money.

50:35.600 --> 50:37.113
I'll do it right now.

50:39.360 --> 50:40.634
Can I use your belt?

50:41.600 --> 50:43.158
(SHIP HORN BLARING)

50:45.800 --> 50:46.800
(BELL DINGING)

50:48.000 --> 50:50.195
The Swingin' Dinghy
is closing, folks.

50:50.280 --> 50:53.716
Time for me to clean up,
time for you to clear out.

50:53.880 --> 50:56.314
So long, fellas.
See ya in eight months.

50:56.480 --> 50:57.799
GIRL 1: Toodle-oo.
GIRL 2: See ya later, boys.

50:57.880 --> 50:59.029
Eight months?

50:59.160 --> 51:00.798
Yeah, we're shipping
out in the morning.

51:00.960 --> 51:03.872
Golly!
Eight months without a dame.

51:04.320 --> 51:05.469
Can you beat it?

51:05.640 --> 51:07.153
You're gonna
have to beat it!

51:11.000 --> 51:12.000
(GIRLS LAUGHING)

51:13.320 --> 51:14.320
(SIGHS)

51:17.160 --> 51:20.596
(SINGING)
We are heading out to sea

51:20.800 --> 51:24.429
And however it'll be

51:24.640 --> 51:29.111
(PIANO PLAYING)
It ain't gonna be the same

51:29.280 --> 51:31.669
'Cause no matter what we see

51:31.840 --> 51:35.037
When we're out
there on the sea

51:35.200 --> 51:39.352
We ain't gonna see a dame

51:41.160 --> 51:42.957
We'll be
searching high and low

51:43.040 --> 51:45.349
On the deck and down below

51:45.520 --> 51:48.751
But it's a crying shame

51:48.920 --> 51:53.436
We'll see a lot of fish
But we'll never clock a dish

51:53.600 --> 51:56.956
We ain't gonna see a dame

51:57.120 --> 51:58.917
No dames

51:59.080 --> 52:01.036
We might see
some octopuses

52:01.200 --> 52:02.838
No dames

52:03.000 --> 52:05.036
Or a half
a dozen clams

52:05.200 --> 52:06.872
No dames

52:07.040 --> 52:09.270
We might even
see a mermaid

52:09.480 --> 52:14.110
ALL: But mermaids
got no gams

52:14.280 --> 52:17.317
No gams

52:23.640 --> 52:26.234
(FEET TAPPING RHYTHMICALLY)

53:05.760 --> 53:07.591
Hey!
Off of there!

53:07.760 --> 53:08.954
Hey, come on.

53:10.640 --> 53:12.312
Hey! Come on.

53:12.480 --> 53:13.480
Hey!

53:13.960 --> 53:15.029
Oh, come on!

53:15.400 --> 53:18.472
Oh, Christ!
Climb up and tappin'.

53:25.280 --> 53:26.280
Ah, come on!

53:58.000 --> 54:00.275
(METALLIC CLINKING)

54:18.800 --> 54:19.800
(BELL RINGING)

54:40.200 --> 54:41.952
SAILOR 1: Have we
got a girl for you!

54:42.640 --> 54:45.154
SAILOR 2: (SINGING)
Out there on the sea

54:45.680 --> 54:48.114
Here's how it will be

54:48.840 --> 54:51.673
I'm gonna
dance with you, pal

54:51.760 --> 54:54.228
You're gonna dance with me

54:54.400 --> 54:55.992
ALL: When we're out
there on the sea

54:56.080 --> 54:57.798
We'll be happy as can be

54:57.960 --> 55:00.599
Or so the captain claims

55:00.760 --> 55:03.672
But we have to disagree
'Cause the only guarantee

55:03.840 --> 55:06.798
Is I'll see a lot of you
And you'll see a lot of me

55:06.960 --> 55:11.829
ALL: And it's absolutely certain
that we'll see a lot of sea

55:12.240 --> 55:15.471
But we ain't
gonna see no dames

55:15.640 --> 55:16.755
SAILOR 2: No dames!

55:16.880 --> 55:18.080
We're gonna see
How will it be?

55:18.120 --> 55:19.712
No dames!
With no dames!

55:19.920 --> 55:21.120
We're gonna see
How will it be?

55:21.200 --> 55:22.872
No dames!
No dames!

55:23.040 --> 55:24.519
We're gonna see
And how will it be?

55:24.680 --> 55:27.148
We ain't gonna see no...

55:34.240 --> 55:35.832
This place looks open!

55:35.920 --> 55:36.920
(SAILORS CHEERING)

55:39.200 --> 55:40.235
What the...

55:49.040 --> 55:50.359
You, out!

55:57.840 --> 55:58.840
(EXCLAIMS)

55:59.000 --> 56:00.149
Stop it! Hey!
Hey!

56:00.320 --> 56:01.514
Quit it!
Cut that out!

56:01.680 --> 56:02.920
This ain't that
kind of a place!

56:04.560 --> 56:05.595
ARNE: Cut!

56:06.680 --> 56:08.477
Yeah, okay.
CREW MEMBER: Okay, kids...

56:08.560 --> 56:09.560
Okay.

56:10.880 --> 56:13.440
Come here, Burt Gurney.
We go again.

56:13.640 --> 56:14.993
Anything different,
Mr. Seslum?

56:15.240 --> 56:16.559
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
No, no, no.

56:16.640 --> 56:18.278
Mostly pretty good,
but this time

56:18.600 --> 56:21.273
don't put dishrag
on bartender's head.

56:21.480 --> 56:23.277
You're a big star,
Burt Gurney.

56:23.480 --> 56:25.152
Who cares about
the bartender?

56:25.360 --> 56:26.679
You are the star.
(SCOFFS)

56:26.760 --> 56:28.193
That's my whole character,
the slow burn.

56:28.320 --> 56:29.719
Gosh, Mr. Seslum,
I don't mind if he wants to...

56:29.800 --> 56:31.074
It is decided.
Hello, Burt.

56:31.640 --> 56:32.834
Hello, Mr. Mannix.

56:33.400 --> 56:35.356
Arne.
Hello.

56:35.520 --> 56:37.750
Listen, I don't wanna stick my
nose in other people's business,

56:37.840 --> 56:39.239
but, uh...

56:39.320 --> 56:43.108
Well, I understand you've been
associating with DeeAnna Moran?

56:43.200 --> 56:44.200
Yeah, yeah,
we associated.

56:44.280 --> 56:45.280
Yes.

56:45.360 --> 56:48.079
But no more, no more.
Don't you worry, Eddie Mannix.

56:48.480 --> 56:50.072
But, Arne, you are
aware that she's...

56:50.240 --> 56:53.152
This must not be in movie magazines,
that we are associated.

56:53.320 --> 56:54.389
No, no,
of course not.

56:54.480 --> 56:55.833
My wife cannot read this.

56:57.040 --> 56:58.109
Your... Excuse me?

56:58.400 --> 56:59.879
Ilsa Pflug.

57:01.040 --> 57:03.235
Ilsa Pflug-Seslum.

57:04.240 --> 57:05.468
In Malm.

57:05.560 --> 57:06.754
I was not aware of that.

57:07.040 --> 57:08.678
ARNE: Yeah, two children.

57:09.160 --> 57:10.880
And a third on the way, apparently.
Mmm-hmm.

57:11.040 --> 57:14.828
Do you enjoy physical culture,
Eddie Mannix? Do you ski?

57:15.920 --> 57:19.356
No. I never took it up.
Seems like a lot of fun, Arne.

57:19.440 --> 57:21.431
I no more associate
with DeeAnna Moran.

57:21.520 --> 57:22.589
I hug you.

57:23.480 --> 57:25.038
Goodbye.

57:25.840 --> 57:27.239
BAIRD: I spent the night.

57:27.320 --> 57:29.993
So, I feel somebody poking at me,
and I wake up and it's Clark.

57:30.080 --> 57:33.516
And he says, "Well, your keys aren't
in there, so I guess we're walking."

57:33.880 --> 57:34.880
(ALL LAUGHING)

57:36.520 --> 57:39.751
This was back before
Gable was Gable.

57:39.840 --> 57:43.230
Yeah, we used to go up to
San Berdoo every weekend.

57:43.320 --> 57:45.276
Bob Stack would
come up sometimes.

57:45.360 --> 57:47.271
Blue Grotto
was still open.

57:47.480 --> 57:49.869
Dave Chasen
was a busboy.

57:50.600 --> 57:52.716
Quite a place.
Yours?

57:52.920 --> 57:55.309
Gracious, no. It belongs to
a member of our study group.

57:55.720 --> 57:57.392
He couldn't be
here this afternoon.

57:57.560 --> 57:58.800
He'll be sad to
have missed you.

57:58.880 --> 57:59.915
He's a fan.

58:00.120 --> 58:01.314
Uh-huh.
That's swell.

58:01.480 --> 58:03.232
So, I black out,
I wake up here...

58:04.200 --> 58:05.200
(WINCES)

58:05.560 --> 58:07.391
And I say to myself,

58:07.560 --> 58:09.835
"Baird, you gotta stop doing this."
(ALL LAUGHING)

58:11.600 --> 58:14.558
But you're saying, actually,
technically, I was kidnapped.

58:14.920 --> 58:17.036
Well, technically, yes.

58:17.400 --> 58:18.549
There's gonna be a ransom?

58:18.680 --> 58:20.159
I'd hardly
call it a ransom.

58:20.240 --> 58:22.913
Benedict there.
That's Benedict de Bonaventure.

58:23.000 --> 58:24.797
He wrote
The House of Ahasuaris.

58:25.080 --> 58:28.675
Enormous hit. Made the
studio millions of dollars.

58:28.760 --> 58:30.990
Did you see any of those
millions of dollars, Ben?

58:31.080 --> 58:32.149
I did not.

58:32.440 --> 58:33.555
Dutch over there.

58:34.000 --> 58:36.673
Dutch Zweistrong wrote
All The Way To Uruguay.

58:36.840 --> 58:38.910
I wrote all the
All The Way pictures.

58:39.080 --> 58:41.992
All successful. You see any of
the profits, Dutch? (SCOFFS)

58:42.600 --> 58:44.591
See, all of us
here are writers.

58:45.440 --> 58:48.432
The pictures originated with us.
They're our ideas.

58:48.600 --> 58:50.079
But they're owned
by the studio.

58:50.960 --> 58:53.872
I'm not saying only writers
are being exploited.

58:53.960 --> 58:55.200
I mean, look at
yourself, Baird.

58:58.440 --> 59:00.431
The studio takes
pretty good care of me.

59:00.640 --> 59:01.868
What are you, a child?

59:02.800 --> 59:05.189
I think what Herschel's
trying to say is,

59:05.360 --> 59:08.318
just because the studio owns
the means of production,

59:08.720 --> 59:13.157
why should it be able to
take the money, our money,

59:13.240 --> 59:15.151
the value created
by our labor,

59:15.280 --> 59:17.555
and dole out
what it pleases?

59:17.640 --> 59:18.789
That's not right.

59:18.960 --> 59:22.157
So, no. No.
I wouldn't call it ransom.

59:22.320 --> 59:23.878
Payback.
WRITER 1: That's right.

59:24.080 --> 59:28.551
Now, until quite recently our
study group had a narrow focus.

59:28.720 --> 59:32.395
We concentrated on getting communist
content into motion pictures.

59:32.560 --> 59:34.676
Always in a sub
rosa way, of course.

59:34.880 --> 59:37.235
And we were
pretty darn successful.

59:37.400 --> 59:39.516
You remember in
Kerner's Corner

59:39.720 --> 59:40.755
the town hall scene
where the alderman

59:40.840 --> 59:42.114
overturned the
rotten election

59:42.200 --> 59:43.918
and made Gus the mayor?

59:44.760 --> 59:45.829
Yeah.

59:46.840 --> 59:50.515
Well, I like to think
we've changed a few minds.

59:51.760 --> 59:55.036
But then Dr. Marcuse came down from
Stanford, joined the study group

59:55.200 --> 59:59.159
and started teaching
us about direct action.

59:59.360 --> 01:00:00.918
Praxis.
Action.

01:00:01.000 --> 01:00:05.551
We each pursue our
own economic interest.

01:00:06.200 --> 01:00:09.317
We ourselves are not above
the laws of history.

01:00:09.840 --> 01:00:14.038
But in pursuing our
interests with vigor,

01:00:14.200 --> 01:00:17.431
we accelerate the dialectic

01:00:17.520 --> 01:00:22.036
and hasten the end of history and
the creation of the New Man.

01:00:22.400 --> 01:00:24.391
Plus, we make a little dough.
DUTCH: Shut up!

01:00:24.720 --> 01:00:26.392
We're not even
talking about money!

01:00:26.480 --> 01:00:28.198
We're talking about economics.

01:00:28.800 --> 01:00:30.472
Sure, good.

01:00:31.440 --> 01:00:33.078
Good stuff.

01:00:35.080 --> 01:00:36.832
So, now, uh, do I get
a share of the ransom?

01:00:36.960 --> 01:00:38.109
No.
(ALL LAUGHING)

01:00:38.200 --> 01:00:42.637
No, Mr. Whitlock, you can hardly
share in your own ransom.

01:00:42.720 --> 01:00:44.153
That would be unethical.

01:00:44.240 --> 01:00:46.231
I don't know. That doesn't
seem fair, fellas.

01:00:46.880 --> 01:00:49.633
I mean, the whole setup only
works if I play along, right?

01:00:50.080 --> 01:00:52.719
If I don't let on that I
know who kidnapped me.

01:00:52.880 --> 01:00:54.199
Well, yes,
that's right.

01:00:54.920 --> 01:00:56.239
What if I name names?

01:00:57.920 --> 01:01:01.071
If I just tell the truth.

01:01:02.920 --> 01:01:03.920
Uh...

01:01:04.480 --> 01:01:07.392
I don't think you'll
do that, Mr. Whitlock.

01:01:09.080 --> 01:01:14.438
What if we told the truth
about On Wings as Eagles?

01:01:20.120 --> 01:01:21.553
EDDIE: Sid.

01:01:22.960 --> 01:01:24.840
We have to work something
out for DeeAnna Moran.

01:01:25.360 --> 01:01:26.429
She get married again?

01:01:26.520 --> 01:01:28.988
No, that's the problem.
Having a child, not married.

01:01:29.120 --> 01:01:30.189
Whew. Tough.

01:01:30.280 --> 01:01:31.349
Yeah, no father.

01:01:31.440 --> 01:01:32.960
Well, of course
there is one somewhere.

01:01:33.360 --> 01:01:34.554
But who knows?
Exactly.

01:01:34.640 --> 01:01:35.755
So is there any way...

01:01:36.120 --> 01:01:37.439
I'm just spitballing here.

01:01:37.760 --> 01:01:40.718
Any way she could
adopt her own child?

01:01:43.720 --> 01:01:45.597
Interesting.
As a single... Mmm-hmm.

01:01:46.040 --> 01:01:48.110
She disappears for a while, reappears.
Uh-huh.

01:01:48.280 --> 01:01:50.316
She wants to share her
blessings, adopt a child.

01:01:50.480 --> 01:01:53.313
Sure. She's always
yearned to be a mother.

01:01:53.800 --> 01:01:54.869
That's it.

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:56.558
Well, I don't see
why not.

01:01:56.640 --> 01:01:57.629
Nothing in the
California statute

01:01:57.680 --> 01:01:59.636
prohibits adoption by one's own parent.
Mmm-hmm.

01:02:00.520 --> 01:02:01.714
This is new ground.

01:02:01.800 --> 01:02:03.392
Technically, she'd have
to give up the baby

01:02:03.480 --> 01:02:05.038
to a third party.

01:02:05.120 --> 01:02:06.314
Joe Silverman.

01:02:06.440 --> 01:02:09.034
Joe Silverman. Exactly.

01:02:09.160 --> 01:02:11.799
He's the foster father
for a few days.

01:02:11.880 --> 01:02:14.553
She hands the kid to Joe,
he hands it back.

01:02:14.880 --> 01:02:16.029
I'll do
some research.

01:02:16.120 --> 01:02:17.120
All right.

01:02:17.360 --> 01:02:19.157
NATALIE:
Mr. Mannix, it's 5:30.

01:02:19.320 --> 01:02:20.514
This is exciting.

01:02:20.680 --> 01:02:23.592
NATALIE:...and asked all of the assistant
directors, and one of them said

01:02:23.680 --> 01:02:27.195
that an extra in the courtyard of
Sestimus Amydias seemed jumpy.

01:02:27.280 --> 01:02:28.633
All right. Get Walt
the name of the extra

01:02:28.720 --> 01:02:30.160
so he can bring
him in and sweat him.

01:02:30.240 --> 01:02:31.593
Walt should tell him that
we won't press charges

01:02:31.680 --> 01:02:32.635
if he tells us where
Baird's been taken.

01:02:32.720 --> 01:02:33.755
NATALIE: Check.

01:02:33.840 --> 01:02:35.831
And if he plays dumb,
or the AD's wrong and he is dumb,

01:02:35.920 --> 01:02:37.148
check the other extras.

01:02:37.240 --> 01:02:38.832
Check. Thessaly Thacker called,
(SIGHS)

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:41.150
said you promised her an
interview with Baird today.

01:02:41.360 --> 01:02:43.078
Check that. It was
Thora Thacker.

01:02:43.160 --> 01:02:44.309
No, it's Thessaly.

01:02:44.400 --> 01:02:45.913
Tell her he was at the
doctor longer than expected,

01:02:46.000 --> 01:02:47.797
and she can see him on the set
bright and early tomorrow.

01:02:47.880 --> 01:02:49.996
Check. And is that
last part true?

01:02:50.120 --> 01:02:51.599
Let's hope so.
Oh, that reminds me.

01:02:51.680 --> 01:02:52.999
I need a list of
everyone who worked on

01:02:53.120 --> 01:02:54.917
On Wings as Eagles
who's still at the studio.

01:02:55.040 --> 01:02:57.031
On Wings as Eagles?
That's a while ago now.

01:02:57.120 --> 01:02:59.190
Aside from Baird and the director,
it won't be a long list.

01:02:59.280 --> 01:03:00.759
Yeah. Get it
for me. That it?

01:03:00.880 --> 01:03:02.757
Uh, no.
One more thing.

01:03:02.880 --> 01:03:04.108
A Mr. Cuddahy called,

01:03:04.200 --> 01:03:05.792
said you know him.
Yeah, yeah.

01:03:05.880 --> 01:03:08.110
He said it's urgent,
he'll see you one last time,

01:03:08.200 --> 01:03:10.430
suggested same place,
7:00 this evening.

01:03:10.520 --> 01:03:12.272
Why? Never mind.

01:03:12.360 --> 01:03:14.715
Okay, tell him
I'll be there.

01:03:14.920 --> 01:03:15.989
CAD: Back to your place?

01:03:16.080 --> 01:03:17.149
WOMAN: What a bore.

01:03:17.240 --> 01:03:18.275
Hello, C.C.

01:03:18.360 --> 01:03:20.160
WOMAN: I rather thought
we might go to Lake...

01:03:20.760 --> 01:03:21.909
Oh, hi, Eddie.

01:03:22.200 --> 01:03:24.040
Wanna lace up what you got
on Merrily We Dance?

01:03:24.200 --> 01:03:26.430
It's up now.
I'll put some music on it.

01:03:29.720 --> 01:03:30.720
(PROJECTOR WHIRRING)

01:03:40.400 --> 01:03:42.436
(MUSIC PLAYING)

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:09.115
CAD: Taxi!

01:04:09.720 --> 01:04:10.720
(TIRES SCREECHING)

01:04:17.640 --> 01:04:19.198
Back to your place?

01:04:19.280 --> 01:04:20.508
What a bore.

01:04:20.600 --> 01:04:23.672
I rather thought we might go to
Lake Onondaga for the weekend.

01:04:23.880 --> 01:04:25.154
Just the two of us.

01:04:25.320 --> 01:04:27.595
Don't have my valise.
I left it in your foyer.

01:04:27.800 --> 01:04:29.756
Oh, you'll get by
without a change.

01:04:29.840 --> 01:04:30.955
Suits me.

01:04:31.040 --> 01:04:32.871
If you don't mind skipping out
on your own party, Allegra.

01:04:32.960 --> 01:04:33.960
Suits me.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:35.433
And skipping out on Monty.

01:04:35.520 --> 01:04:37.351
That suits me as well.

01:04:37.440 --> 01:04:39.396
Oh, poor Monty.
(BOTH CH UCKLING)

01:04:39.520 --> 01:04:40.873
What Monty
doesn't know...

01:04:40.960 --> 01:04:42.109
Won 't hurt Monty.

01:04:56.840 --> 01:04:57.875
DIERDRE: Oh, Monty.

01:04:58.560 --> 01:05:00.152
Come join me
on the divan.

01:05:10.200 --> 01:05:13.476
It seems Allegra's a no-show,
which is simply a bore.

01:05:13.680 --> 01:05:14.680
But I'll...

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:21.000
(C.C CALHOUN CHOKING)

01:05:24.160 --> 01:05:25.160
(FEEBLY) Reverse.

01:05:26.760 --> 01:05:28.398
(STRAINING)
Reverse! Reverse!

01:05:30.920 --> 01:05:31.920
(EXCLAIMING)

01:05:32.480 --> 01:05:33.480
Whoa!

01:05:35.360 --> 01:05:36.952
Whoa!
(CHAIR THUDS)

01:05:42.200 --> 01:05:43.872
I shouldn't wear scarves.

01:05:53.600 --> 01:05:56.876
It seems Allegra's a no-show,
which is simply a bore.

01:05:57.200 --> 01:05:59.031
But I'll partner
you in bridge.

01:05:59.520 --> 01:06:00.953
Why the pout?

01:06:04.040 --> 01:06:05.040
(CLICKS TONGUE)

01:06:09.040 --> 01:06:10.712
It's complicated.

01:06:11.720 --> 01:06:13.836
How pleasant to see
you again, Mr. Mannix.

01:06:15.400 --> 01:06:16.833
Thanks for
coming back, Mannix.

01:06:16.920 --> 01:06:18.239
EDDIE: Sure.

01:06:18.320 --> 01:06:20.080
You're taking us down
to the wire, aren't ya?

01:06:21.120 --> 01:06:23.634
It's not a ploy,
it's a big decision.

01:06:23.720 --> 01:06:25.073
Absolutely. No foul.

01:06:25.160 --> 01:06:26.200
But the board
was concerned

01:06:26.240 --> 01:06:27.798
when I couldn't give them
a yes this afternoon,

01:06:27.920 --> 01:06:29.717
so they authorized me
to say this.

01:06:30.840 --> 01:06:34.230
You sign on, your term
of contract is 10 years.

01:06:34.880 --> 01:06:35.880
(WHISTLES)

01:06:35.960 --> 01:06:38.155
Yeah. You get it, right?

01:06:38.240 --> 01:06:40.674
That means your stock options
are guaranteed to vest.

01:06:40.760 --> 01:06:41.920
You'd never
have to work again

01:06:42.000 --> 01:06:44.036
if you chose to retire
after your term.

01:06:44.640 --> 01:06:46.392
Think about it.

01:06:46.520 --> 01:06:48.511
Lifetime employment.

01:06:48.600 --> 01:06:50.670
You wouldn't be a glorified
working stiff like you are now,

01:06:50.760 --> 01:06:52.560
and you'd be running a business,
not a circus.

01:06:55.280 --> 01:06:56.280
Drink?

01:06:57.920 --> 01:06:58.920
Cigarette?

01:07:03.640 --> 01:07:05.358
No, no. I gotta run.

01:07:05.680 --> 01:07:07.272
I should talk this
over with my wife.

01:07:07.360 --> 01:07:09.280
Of course. Talk it over,
think about your family,

01:07:09.600 --> 01:07:10.953
let us know
in the morning.

01:07:11.040 --> 01:07:12.553
Oh! (CHUCKLES)

01:07:12.640 --> 01:07:14.039
If you think
this is a bribe,

01:07:14.120 --> 01:07:15.519
you're absolutely right.

01:07:15.680 --> 01:07:16.829
You have two kids, right?
A boy and a girl?

01:07:16.920 --> 01:07:17.989
That's right.

01:07:18.280 --> 01:07:21.670
They love this stuff.
Used to be trains.

01:07:21.840 --> 01:07:24.798
(MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO)

01:08:23.359 --> 01:08:24.395
CARLOTTA: Hello, Hobie.

01:08:25.200 --> 01:08:27.031
Oh, hello, Carlotta.

01:08:27.120 --> 01:08:28.120
Am I late?

01:08:28.520 --> 01:08:29.714
Oh, no, it ain't nothin'.

01:08:29.800 --> 01:08:32.109
Thanks an awful bunch for
coming to this picture with me.

01:08:32.200 --> 01:08:33.679
I don't know if
you like livestock,

01:08:33.760 --> 01:08:35.955
but I think it's got
moments, I really do.

01:08:36.040 --> 01:08:37.154
You look very purty.

01:08:37.240 --> 01:08:38.354
Thank you, Hobie!

01:08:38.439 --> 01:08:39.475
I'm sure I'll
like the picture.

01:08:39.560 --> 01:08:40.959
I like all of your pictures.

01:08:41.040 --> 01:08:42.040
Well, I like yours, too.

01:08:42.120 --> 01:08:44.076
They are just
the craziest things.

01:08:44.160 --> 01:08:46.720
Uh, is it hard to dance with
all them bananas on your head?

01:08:46.800 --> 01:08:48.791
Oh, no.
Anyone can do it.

01:08:51.800 --> 01:08:54.240
It's all in the hips and the lips
and the eyes and the thighs.

01:08:56.200 --> 01:08:57.200
(DOOR OPENING)

01:09:23.359 --> 01:09:26.272
Little Eddie wanted me to tell
you about his baseball game.

01:09:26.359 --> 01:09:28.316
They won.

01:09:28.399 --> 01:09:29.957
That is terrific.

01:09:30.080 --> 01:09:32.149
(SIGHS) Gosh, I never
called the coach.

01:09:32.240 --> 01:09:33.309
Eddie played at shortstop?

01:09:33.560 --> 01:09:36.596
Mmm. And he did so well,
he wants to stay there now.

01:09:36.880 --> 01:09:38.438
That's great.

01:09:38.720 --> 01:09:39.993
Took care of itself.

01:09:40.479 --> 01:09:43.233
And Darlene did very well
on her Spanish test.

01:09:43.319 --> 01:09:45.993
That's good.
She was worried about that.

01:09:46.960 --> 01:09:48.678
Hey, thanks for heating
up the roast, hon.

01:09:48.760 --> 01:09:49.828
Warm glass of milk?

01:09:49.920 --> 01:09:51.433
Uh, no, thanks,
hon. Coffee.

01:09:51.920 --> 01:09:53.511
I gotta run back
to the studio.

01:09:53.600 --> 01:09:54.720
A few things
to take care of.

01:09:55.520 --> 01:09:58.159
Gee, another late night.
Hmm.

01:10:00.200 --> 01:10:02.998
You know, Lockheed
improved their offer.

01:10:03.560 --> 01:10:04.560
Darned good money,

01:10:04.600 --> 01:10:06.955
and the hours wouldn't be
crazy like this either.

01:10:07.120 --> 01:10:08.872
It's nice
to be wanted.

01:10:09.640 --> 01:10:11.949
Yeah. Sure, but...

01:10:13.640 --> 01:10:15.551
What do you think?
They wanna know tomorrow.

01:10:16.320 --> 01:10:17.389
(SIGHS)

01:10:17.480 --> 01:10:19.277
I like the shorter hours.

01:10:19.960 --> 01:10:21.996
But what do you think, honey?
You know best.

01:10:22.800 --> 01:10:23.800
Hmm.

01:10:25.800 --> 01:10:27.472
How's it going with
the smoking, dear?

01:10:29.240 --> 01:10:30.593
Oh, you know...

01:10:34.800 --> 01:10:40.238
NARRATOR: The denizens of Los Angeles
make ready for nightlife, or for sleep.

01:10:40.400 --> 01:10:43.073
But Eddie Mannix
will have neither.

01:10:45.480 --> 01:10:49.075
Even in westerly Malibu,
the sun has moved on,

01:10:49.240 --> 01:10:50.912
leaving the vast
and tireless sea

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:54.515
to heave itself
blindly upon the shore.

01:10:58.280 --> 01:11:00.919
The communists welcome
a rare moment of leisure.

01:11:01.000 --> 01:11:03.355
Brief surcease from struggle.

01:11:07.680 --> 01:11:10.478
Baird Whitlock has
become their acolyte,

01:11:10.560 --> 01:11:12.357
a convert to their cause,

01:11:12.440 --> 01:11:15.193
his belief compelled
but not grudging.

01:11:16.600 --> 01:11:20.115
He now seeks to learn more
from Professor Marcuse

01:11:20.200 --> 01:11:22.031
and becomes
ever more committed

01:11:22.120 --> 01:11:24.588
to the quest to hasten
an end to history

01:11:25.640 --> 01:11:27.517
and bring on the New Man.

01:11:27.880 --> 01:11:29.438
Herb, that's exactly
what I'm talking about.

01:11:29.520 --> 01:11:31.511
That's what happened to me when
I went to Reno with Danny Kaye,

01:11:31.640 --> 01:11:33.278
and he asked me
to shave his back.

01:11:33.360 --> 01:11:34.634
The exact same thing.

01:11:34.720 --> 01:11:36.358
Because I'm thinking,
"Who benefits?"

01:11:36.520 --> 01:11:39.910
Also, I gotta tell ya, everybody
thinks that Danny is a jerk.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:41.479
He's not really a jerk.

01:11:41.640 --> 01:11:44.837
It's just the theory generating
its own anti-theory.

01:11:45.120 --> 01:11:46.792
Anyway, there we were,
it's me and Danny,

01:11:46.960 --> 01:11:48.279
and I'm wondering
what the hell am I doing

01:11:48.360 --> 01:11:49.554
with a razor
in my hand.

01:11:49.760 --> 01:11:51.990
And he says it's for
a Norman Taurog picture.

01:11:52.120 --> 01:11:54.429
But Judy Canova is there,
and she knows Norman.

01:11:54.520 --> 01:11:56.600
She says, "Danny's not doing
a Norman Taurog picture.

01:11:56.720 --> 01:11:58.836
"He just wants you
to shave his back!"

01:11:59.320 --> 01:12:00.639
And that's who benefits.

01:12:05.040 --> 01:12:06.837
NARRATOR:
In livelier precincts,

01:12:06.920 --> 01:12:09.832
the swells of Dreamland
gather to inspect

01:12:09.920 --> 01:12:12.957
the completed weave
of another piece of gossamer.

01:12:13.040 --> 01:12:14.837
Another movie,

01:12:14.920 --> 01:12:17.309
another portion of balm

01:12:17.400 --> 01:12:20.915
for the ache of
a toiling mankind.

01:12:26.400 --> 01:12:27.515
CURLY: Where is she?

01:12:27.600 --> 01:12:29.079
Hold your horses,
I'm right here.

01:12:29.160 --> 01:12:30.513
What's on your
mind, Curly?

01:12:30.600 --> 01:12:32.670
CURLY: It's not my fault
you saw me take

01:12:32.760 --> 01:12:35.194
that pie off the sill,
Ms. McGraw.

01:12:35.280 --> 01:12:38.272
Not your fault? Whose
fault was it, Curly?

01:12:38.360 --> 01:12:42.672
Why, that crazy,
lazy full moon!

01:12:43.320 --> 01:12:45.834
Two weeks ago, you'd
never seen me take it.

01:12:46.120 --> 01:12:47.120
(CHUCKLES)

01:12:49.600 --> 01:12:52.398
Darn you, moon!
What good are you anyway?

01:12:53.080 --> 01:12:54.120
Don't know
about this part.

01:12:54.160 --> 01:12:56.720
They only give me
one shot at the song.

01:12:56.800 --> 01:12:58.711
I wish there
never was no moon.

01:12:59.040 --> 01:13:01.793
I wish there weren't
no bossy old women!

01:13:01.960 --> 01:13:06.033
Don't blame that moon, Curly.
She can't do nothin' but shine.

01:13:06.120 --> 01:13:10.796
(SINGING)
Lazy ol' moon, keep shinin'

01:13:11.240 --> 01:13:12.593
Darn you.

01:13:12.880 --> 01:13:14.393
HOBIE:
Shinin' down on me

01:13:14.480 --> 01:13:18.792
You turned Curly Strimlin in to the
authorities for the last time!

01:13:20.040 --> 01:13:22.156
HOBIE: Lazy ol' moon,
keep shinin'

01:13:26.040 --> 01:13:30.636
Shinin'just to be

01:13:33.240 --> 01:13:39.759
On that ol' plantation
where I used to roam

01:13:39.920 --> 01:13:43.595
Light my weary
way back home

01:13:46.160 --> 01:13:48.230
Darn! Where'd she go?

01:13:48.360 --> 01:13:50.954
HOBIE: Lazy ol' moon,
keep shinin'

01:13:53.120 --> 01:13:56.476
Shinin' down for me

01:14:07.680 --> 01:14:09.989
(SIRENS WAILING)

01:14:12.600 --> 01:14:16.309
NARRATOR: Another part of town,
another cast of characters,

01:14:18.280 --> 01:14:21.272
another task
for Eddie Mannix.

01:14:35.960 --> 01:14:37.632
We're just
getting started.

01:14:37.720 --> 01:14:39.790
I've been taking
DeeAnna through this.

01:14:39.880 --> 01:14:41.791
So Joe has done

01:14:41.880 --> 01:14:44.599
just a whole lot of good
work for us in the past.

01:14:44.680 --> 01:14:46.875
Whenever we've needed a witness
or a third party for...

01:14:47.800 --> 01:14:51.190
I don't know, a petition of grievance
or alienation of affection.

01:14:51.640 --> 01:14:52.834
And he's reliable?

01:14:52.920 --> 01:14:54.194
I'm bonded, miss.

01:14:54.280 --> 01:14:55.998
Joseph Silverman is the
most reliable human being

01:14:56.080 --> 01:14:58.230
on the planet
in our experience.

01:14:58.440 --> 01:15:00.271
When Chubby Cregar
was intoxicated

01:15:00.360 --> 01:15:02.157
and hit that
pedestrian on Gower,

01:15:02.680 --> 01:15:04.680
we had the vehicle title
transferred to Joe's name,

01:15:05.360 --> 01:15:07.794
and Joe did six months
in LA County lockup.

01:15:08.760 --> 01:15:10.159
But you're off
the sauce now?

01:15:10.520 --> 01:15:12.590
I never touch it.
It was a legal fiction.

01:15:12.760 --> 01:15:13.909
That's right.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:15.149
When the studio needs
someone who meets

01:15:15.280 --> 01:15:16.838
the legal standard of, uh...

01:15:16.920 --> 01:15:18.069
How did you put it, Sid?

01:15:18.680 --> 01:15:19.999
Personhood.

01:15:20.080 --> 01:15:23.789
Joe steps in and
acts as the person.

01:15:25.120 --> 01:15:27.873
So you're a
professional person?

01:15:28.080 --> 01:15:30.913
That's right, miss.
Initial here and here.

01:15:31.080 --> 01:15:33.310
SID: Joe will be the foster
parent until such time as

01:15:33.400 --> 01:15:34.594
you adopt the child,

01:15:34.800 --> 01:15:37.951
which you can do as soon as
Joe takes possession of it.

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:40.274
And he's reliable?

01:15:40.400 --> 01:15:41.628
I'm bonded, miss.

01:15:42.360 --> 01:15:43.349
The release papers
you're signing

01:15:43.440 --> 01:15:45.192
will not be a matter
of public record.

01:15:45.360 --> 01:15:49.114
All these documents will be
sealed until the year 2015.

01:15:50.240 --> 01:15:51.639
And no one's
the wiser.

01:15:51.840 --> 01:15:53.034
SID: No one the wiser.

01:15:53.240 --> 01:15:57.119
No fans, no press, no court officials,
not even a notary public.

01:15:57.480 --> 01:15:59.311
EDDIE: Joe himself
is the notary.

01:16:01.560 --> 01:16:03.357
You must have
very strong forearms.

01:16:05.120 --> 01:16:07.076
Is it hard
squeezing it like that?

01:16:12.400 --> 01:16:13.992
It's part of the job, miss.

01:16:20.600 --> 01:16:22.397
Late night, Mr. Mannix?

01:16:22.480 --> 01:16:23.913
Late night for both of us.

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:25.228
Will you call Projection
Seven and have them

01:16:25.320 --> 01:16:27.550
lace up yesterday's
dailies on Hail, Caesar!

01:16:27.640 --> 01:16:29.392
Sure thing.
Yesterday's?

01:16:29.520 --> 01:16:30.748
Thanks, Scotty.

01:16:33.680 --> 01:16:34.680
(GRUNTING)

01:16:36.120 --> 01:16:40.352
AUTOLOCHUS: Romans before slaves!
Make room, you fools!

01:16:41.440 --> 01:16:43.431
Romans before slaves!

01:16:44.840 --> 01:16:47.513
Romans before slaves!

01:16:49.040 --> 01:16:50.234
Make room!

01:17:04.400 --> 01:17:05.992
How's that? What do you think?
DIRECTOR: Cut!

01:17:06.080 --> 01:17:07.195
CLAPPER BOY: 27, Baker two.

01:17:07.280 --> 01:17:08.315
DIRECTOR: Action.

01:17:08.400 --> 01:17:09.958
Go ahead,
I'm listening.

01:17:10.240 --> 01:17:12.435
Walt talked to the
extra. Right guy.

01:17:12.720 --> 01:17:14.631
No info. Doesn't know
where they took Baird,

01:17:14.720 --> 01:17:17.518
but described the truck
they put him in.

01:17:17.600 --> 01:17:18.715
DIRECTOR: Cut! Good!

01:17:18.960 --> 01:17:21.679
Walt found the guy who owns the
truck and is talking to him.

01:17:21.840 --> 01:17:22.989
CLAPPER BOY: Baker four.

01:17:23.080 --> 01:17:25.400
Walt's a problem-solver. He's a good man.
DIRECTOR: Action!

01:17:25.640 --> 01:17:26.789
What else?

01:17:26.880 --> 01:17:29.553
PR just called in their report
on the Hobie Doyle premiere.

01:17:29.680 --> 01:17:31.079
Warm reception.

01:17:31.160 --> 01:17:32.680
I got something... I had spittle.
Good.

01:17:32.880 --> 01:17:34.552
CLAPPER BOY: Baker six.
DIRECTOR: Action.

01:17:34.640 --> 01:17:36.232
Okay.
He's terrific.

01:17:37.040 --> 01:17:39.349
DIRECTOR: Squint! Squint
against the grandeur.

01:17:39.560 --> 01:17:40.560
It's blinding! Blinding!

01:17:42.040 --> 01:17:44.156
(MUSIC PLAYING)
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

01:17:50.160 --> 01:17:52.549
HOBIE: Now, let's see
what we can do here.

01:17:53.880 --> 01:17:55.313
Okay.

01:17:55.440 --> 01:17:59.513
Well, I don't think it's regulation size,
but it'll have to do.

01:17:59.640 --> 01:18:02.438
You ever heard of origami,
what the Japanese do? Uh-huh.

01:18:03.120 --> 01:18:04.519
This here's
Italian origami.

01:18:05.080 --> 01:18:06.149
Yeah?

01:18:06.240 --> 01:18:07.912
See, now you just...
Whoop!

01:18:08.760 --> 01:18:10.591
Let's see how
she does now.

01:18:12.760 --> 01:18:14.273
Oh, she's peekin' back.

01:18:14.400 --> 01:18:15.833
Oh! There she goes.

01:18:16.280 --> 01:18:17.280
(LAUGHING)

01:18:17.360 --> 01:18:18.360
She's bawlin'.

01:18:20.000 --> 01:18:21.149
Clear!
Ah!

01:18:21.960 --> 01:18:24.793
This is why I never
order it with meat sauce.

01:18:24.960 --> 01:18:26.518
How'd you get into
pictures, Hobie?

01:18:26.720 --> 01:18:27.994
Got roped into it.

01:18:30.720 --> 01:18:31.869
(LAUGHING) Stop!

01:18:34.880 --> 01:18:38.429
Don't play
with your food.

01:18:39.800 --> 01:18:40.835
Food!

01:18:41.360 --> 01:18:42.395
You're the one
playing with it.

01:18:42.480 --> 01:18:43.708
Stop it!

01:18:44.120 --> 01:18:45.951
Pictures. Well,
I wrangled for a while,

01:18:46.040 --> 01:18:48.156
and then they saw I
could say a line or two,

01:18:48.320 --> 01:18:50.436
and I was Bad Clem
or Deputy Number Two

01:18:50.520 --> 01:18:52.636
or a guy's buddy
for a couple of years,

01:18:52.800 --> 01:18:56.236
and then someone heard me sing
and they made me the guy.

01:18:56.400 --> 01:18:57.674
You're awfully cute.

01:18:57.840 --> 01:19:00.638
Oh, heck, you ain't seen the half of it.
I'll show you cute.

01:19:00.840 --> 01:19:04.310
Just a second here,
a little souvenir from my rodeo days.

01:19:08.560 --> 01:19:10.118
(LAUGHING)

01:19:10.200 --> 01:19:12.077
Tell you what,
I was steer-bustin',

01:19:12.160 --> 01:19:13.388
and I went down and
the steer went up,

01:19:13.480 --> 01:19:16.040
and my teeth headed
off for east Texas.

01:19:16.240 --> 01:19:17.992
Here, it's coming
around again.

01:19:18.800 --> 01:19:19.800
Whoo!

01:19:22.560 --> 01:19:24.357
(SINGING)
You gotta give a little

01:19:24.440 --> 01:19:25.668
Take a little

01:19:26.000 --> 01:19:28.673
BOTH: And let your poor
heart break a little

01:19:28.840 --> 01:19:30.159
That's the story of...

01:19:30.360 --> 01:19:31.680
CARLOTTA:
That's the glory of love

01:19:34.720 --> 01:19:38.235
You gotta laugh a little,
cry a little

01:19:38.400 --> 01:19:40.118
And let the clouds
roll by a...

01:19:40.960 --> 01:19:42.518
Well, now,
this is interesting.

01:19:42.600 --> 01:19:44.238
I didn't know you
two were friends.

01:19:45.280 --> 01:19:46.599
Oh, heck, yeah.

01:19:46.800 --> 01:19:49.917
We just caught my picture Lazy Ol' Moon,
and I guess we're...

01:19:50.960 --> 01:19:53.076
Yes, we're
friends. We're...

01:19:53.240 --> 01:19:54.920
We're fixin' to be friendly,
tell you that.

01:19:55.720 --> 01:19:56.994
That's good.

01:19:57.080 --> 01:19:58.229
"Fixin' to be friendly."

01:19:58.320 --> 01:20:00.197
That can be my
column headline.

01:20:00.800 --> 01:20:02.153
Oh, I guess
that'd be okay.

01:20:02.240 --> 01:20:03.434
Have a good evening.

01:20:03.720 --> 01:20:04.720
(EXHALES)

01:20:05.400 --> 01:20:06.674
I mentioned
the name of my picture.

01:20:06.760 --> 01:20:08.080
I think we're
supposed to do that.

01:20:08.240 --> 01:20:09.440
Well, now,
this is interesting.

01:20:12.320 --> 01:20:14.390
I thought I was getting
an exclusive on this.

01:20:14.560 --> 01:20:16.869
I'd like to know what the
hell is going on here.

01:20:17.240 --> 01:20:20.437
Oh, well, like I said, we just
saw Lazy Ol' Moon, and...

01:20:20.600 --> 01:20:23.319
And Hobie and I are
fixin' to be friendly.

01:20:23.800 --> 01:20:25.392
What?
HOBIE: We're just...

01:20:25.480 --> 01:20:27.232
THORA: Friends, my foot!

01:20:36.800 --> 01:20:37.869
What's the matter, Hobie?

01:20:40.160 --> 01:20:42.310
I gotta skedaddle.
So sorry. Oh!

01:20:42.520 --> 01:20:43.509
Have to catch one of
your pictures next time.

01:20:43.600 --> 01:20:44.999
I'm looking
forward to it.

01:20:45.080 --> 01:20:46.229
CARLOTTA: Bye, Hobie.

01:20:47.440 --> 01:20:49.431
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

01:20:58.280 --> 01:20:59.713
Hey, toss me
them keys, pard.

01:20:59.800 --> 01:21:00.949
I'm taking the car.

01:23:00.040 --> 01:23:01.553
Hobie Doyle?

01:23:02.120 --> 01:23:03.599
You're a communist, too?

01:23:06.960 --> 01:23:08.916
So, it's commies.

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:11.309
You ever been in this place?
Pretty nice, huh?

01:23:11.400 --> 01:23:12.992
It's Burt Gurney's.

01:23:13.080 --> 01:23:15.913
He sings, he dances,
he's got taste.

01:23:18.240 --> 01:23:19.753
You here alone?

01:23:19.920 --> 01:23:21.672
Everybody else went
down to the beach.

01:23:23.320 --> 01:23:24.799
Well, all right, pard.

01:23:26.760 --> 01:23:28.910
Let's us head on
back to town.

01:23:29.080 --> 01:23:31.435
You got Mr. Mannix
worried sick.

01:23:36.640 --> 01:23:38.676
(DOG BARKING)

01:23:58.960 --> 01:24:00.109
Easy.

01:24:06.320 --> 01:24:07.435
Easy.

01:24:12.080 --> 01:24:13.080
Here!

01:24:43.080 --> 01:24:44.593
(EXHALES)

01:24:46.840 --> 01:24:48.751
(WATER GURGLING)

01:24:48.920 --> 01:24:52.629
(SONAR BEEPING)

01:26:04.800 --> 01:26:07.633
(BARKING)

01:26:21.600 --> 01:26:23.477
Take care of him.

01:26:31.200 --> 01:26:32.758
Comrade. Comrade!

01:26:33.160 --> 01:26:35.116
We salute you.

01:26:35.480 --> 01:26:38.313
You are going to Moscow
to become Soviet Man

01:26:38.480 --> 01:26:39.959
and help forge the future.

01:26:40.600 --> 01:26:44.036
We stay behind, continuing
to serve in our disguise

01:26:44.120 --> 01:26:46.315
as capitalist handmaidens.

01:26:46.480 --> 01:26:48.914
But the money should
go to the cause,

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:50.433
not to the servants
of the cause.

01:26:50.640 --> 01:26:51.868
ALL: Yes!
That's right.

01:26:51.960 --> 01:26:53.234
We... Well...

01:26:54.040 --> 01:26:57.635
Our modest contribution
to the Comintern.

01:27:04.160 --> 01:27:05.479
They will be pleased.

01:27:06.680 --> 01:27:07.680
(ENGELS BARKING)

01:27:09.160 --> 01:27:10.354
No! No!

01:27:11.200 --> 01:27:12.428
Engels!

01:27:14.040 --> 01:27:15.040
(ALL GASPING)

01:27:18.200 --> 01:27:19.235
(WHIMPERING) No.

01:27:22.280 --> 01:27:23.280
(ALL SIGHING)

01:27:26.480 --> 01:27:29.472
(SUBMARINE SIRENS BLARING)

01:27:34.600 --> 01:27:36.830
(MEN GRUNTING)

01:27:39.720 --> 01:27:40.720
(SONAR BEEPING)

01:28:16.560 --> 01:28:17.560
Oh.

01:28:27.720 --> 01:28:30.234
BAIRD: Oh, boy! It's late.
I'm in the doghouse.

01:28:30.400 --> 01:28:32.277
Better forget
about my place.

01:28:32.440 --> 01:28:34.396
Drop me off at the Beverly Hills Hotel.
(POLICE SIRENS BLARING)

01:28:34.560 --> 01:28:35.879
HOBIE: All righty.

01:28:50.120 --> 01:28:51.120
Huh.

01:29:19.640 --> 01:29:21.039
Who are you?

01:29:21.200 --> 01:29:22.349
Todd.

01:29:23.120 --> 01:29:24.348
Todd.

01:29:25.120 --> 01:29:27.270
You get a hot breakfast
or a box breakfast?

01:29:28.600 --> 01:29:29.874
I don't know.

01:29:30.480 --> 01:29:32.436
Are you a principal
or an extra?

01:29:33.600 --> 01:29:35.272
I think
I'm a principal.

01:29:35.440 --> 01:29:36.668
Yeah.

01:29:37.840 --> 01:29:39.193
BAIRD: I'm thinking,
"What the hell?"

01:29:39.280 --> 01:29:40.800
Woken up in some
strange houses before,

01:29:41.280 --> 01:29:42.793
but never without
a broad next to me.

01:29:43.440 --> 01:29:45.954
Mmm-hmm. These guys are
pretty interesting, though.

01:29:46.040 --> 01:29:49.999
They've actually figured out the
laws that dictate everything.

01:29:50.080 --> 01:29:53.675
History, sociology, politics,
morality, everything.

01:29:53.840 --> 01:29:56.877
It's all in a book
called Kapital, with a "K."

01:29:57.040 --> 01:29:58.314
That right?

01:29:58.400 --> 01:29:59.674
Yeah. And you're not
gonna believe this.

01:29:59.840 --> 01:30:01.432
These guys even figured out

01:30:01.520 --> 01:30:03.158
what's going on
here at the studio,

01:30:03.320 --> 01:30:05.515
because the studio
is nothing more

01:30:05.600 --> 01:30:08.273
than an instrument of capitalism.
Hmm.

01:30:08.360 --> 01:30:12.672
Yeah, so we blindly follow these
laws like any other institution,

01:30:12.880 --> 01:30:14.757
laws that these
guys figured out.

01:30:14.840 --> 01:30:17.638
The studio makes pictures
to serve the system.

01:30:17.720 --> 01:30:19.073
That is its function.

01:30:19.320 --> 01:30:21.151
That's really what
we're up to here.

01:30:21.520 --> 01:30:22.839
Is it?
Yeah.

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:25.992
It's just confirming what
they call the "status quo."

01:30:26.440 --> 01:30:29.113
I mean, we may tell ourselves
that we're creating

01:30:29.200 --> 01:30:31.156
something of artistic value,

01:30:31.360 --> 01:30:35.353
or there's some sort of spiritual
dimension to the picture business.

01:30:35.520 --> 01:30:38.239
But what it really is,
is this fat cat,

01:30:38.360 --> 01:30:39.759
Nick Schenk,
out in New York,

01:30:39.920 --> 01:30:43.356
running this factory,
serving up these lollipops to the...

01:30:43.520 --> 01:30:45.720
What they used to call the
bread and circuses for the...

01:30:48.600 --> 01:30:49.669
What...

01:30:50.200 --> 01:30:51.200
(GRUNTS)

01:30:51.440 --> 01:30:52.668
Now, you listen
to me, buster.

01:30:53.080 --> 01:30:54.672
Nick Schenk and this studio
have been good to you

01:30:54.880 --> 01:30:56.359
and to everyone else
who works here.

01:30:56.520 --> 01:30:58.440
If I ever hear you bad-mouthing
Mr. Schenk again,

01:30:58.560 --> 01:30:59.913
it will be the last
thing you say

01:31:00.000 --> 01:31:00.955
before I have you
tossed in jail

01:31:01.040 --> 01:31:02.440
for colluding in
your own abduction.

01:31:02.480 --> 01:31:04.160
Eddie, I wouldn't...
I would never do that!

01:31:05.200 --> 01:31:06.235
Shut up!

01:31:06.400 --> 01:31:08.436
You're gonna go out there and
you're gonna finish Hail, Caesar!

01:31:08.560 --> 01:31:09.515
You're gonna
give that speech

01:31:09.600 --> 01:31:10.589
at the feet of the
penitent thief,

01:31:10.680 --> 01:31:12.432
and you're gonna believe
every word you say.

01:31:12.720 --> 01:31:13.720
(GRUNTING)

01:31:14.000 --> 01:31:15.115
You're gonna do it
because you're an actor

01:31:15.240 --> 01:31:16.275
and that's what you do,

01:31:16.360 --> 01:31:17.998
just like the director
does what he does,

01:31:18.080 --> 01:31:19.069
and the writer
and the script girl

01:31:19.200 --> 01:31:20.440
and the guy who
claps the slate.

01:31:20.480 --> 01:31:22.400
You're gonna do it because
the picture has worth!

01:31:22.560 --> 01:31:24.152
And you have worth if
you serve the picture,

01:31:24.240 --> 01:31:26.196
and you're never gonna
forget that again.

01:31:26.360 --> 01:31:27.360
(MUMBLING)

01:31:29.000 --> 01:31:30.479
I won't forget, Eddie.

01:31:31.240 --> 01:31:33.071
You're damn right
you won't.

01:31:33.240 --> 01:31:35.276
Not as long as
I run this dump.

01:31:39.600 --> 01:31:41.192
(DOOR OPENS)
Baird.

01:31:45.760 --> 01:31:47.751
Go out there
and be a star.

01:31:49.240 --> 01:31:50.434
NATALIE: Mr. Mannix!

01:31:52.360 --> 01:31:53.475
Since you're
going to your car,

01:31:53.560 --> 01:31:54.993
I thought you might
wanna take this.

01:31:55.080 --> 01:31:56.195
What is it?

01:31:56.320 --> 01:31:57.639
From DeeAnna Moran.

01:31:57.800 --> 01:31:59.199
Thank you, and she
doesn't need to

01:31:59.280 --> 01:32:00.998
adopt her baby
after all.

01:32:01.080 --> 01:32:02.115
Huh?

01:32:02.440 --> 01:32:04.510
She asked Joe Silverman out
for dinner last night,

01:32:04.600 --> 01:32:06.033
and I guess
it went well.

01:32:06.200 --> 01:32:07.269
They drove to
Palm Springs

01:32:07.360 --> 01:32:09.510
and were married at
3:00 this morning.

01:32:09.600 --> 01:32:11.192
Huh.
(SIGHS)

01:32:11.280 --> 01:32:13.191
Will you be gone long?
Today's call list to go through.

01:32:13.280 --> 01:32:15.510
No, less than an hour.
Personal errand.

01:32:15.600 --> 01:32:17.113
It's a nice arrangement.

01:32:17.280 --> 01:32:18.838
She charged it
to the studio.

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:20.513
Right. (GASPS)

01:32:21.120 --> 01:32:22.155
Just coming to see you.

01:32:22.280 --> 01:32:23.429
Good morning. Uh...

01:32:23.640 --> 01:32:26.440
Sorry about last night, Thora.
I didn't know your sister would show up.

01:32:26.880 --> 01:32:29.394
Well, that's as may be, but I
certainly learned my lesson.

01:32:29.680 --> 01:32:31.557
Whatever you say today,
Eddie Mannix,

01:32:31.640 --> 01:32:33.119
my column tomorrow
is about

01:32:34.120 --> 01:32:36.111
On Wings as Eagles.

01:32:36.320 --> 01:32:37.673
Thora, I wouldn't do
that if I were you.

01:32:37.840 --> 01:32:38.989
I'm sure you wouldn't.

01:32:39.160 --> 01:32:41.754
No, no, no, you don't understand.
Let's sit down.

01:32:42.160 --> 01:32:44.958
I'm telling you not to run the column,
Thora, for your own good.

01:32:45.160 --> 01:32:46.195
(LAUGHS)

01:32:46.280 --> 01:32:47.554
I can judge
my own interest.

01:32:47.640 --> 01:32:49.471
This will be
the story of the year.

01:32:49.640 --> 01:32:51.232
And it so happens
the Hearst syndicate

01:32:51.320 --> 01:32:53.311
are looking to pick up
a Hollywood column.

01:32:53.480 --> 01:32:54.515
And you think this
will cinch it for you?

01:32:54.600 --> 01:32:55.600
You know it will.

01:32:56.120 --> 01:32:58.759
Baird Whitlock,
your biggest star,

01:32:58.880 --> 01:33:01.519
got his first major part
in On Wings as Eagles

01:33:01.600 --> 01:33:03.238
by engaging in sodomy

01:33:04.440 --> 01:33:07.273
with the picture's director,
Laurence Laurentz.

01:33:07.360 --> 01:33:08.918
Oh, we've all
heard the story.

01:33:09.160 --> 01:33:10.991
But here's something
you haven't heard.

01:33:11.160 --> 01:33:13.435
Your source
is a communist.

01:33:14.200 --> 01:33:15.428
If you print it,
it'll be dismissed

01:33:15.520 --> 01:33:16.555
as a commie smear tactic,

01:33:16.720 --> 01:33:19.109
and you'll be dismissed
as a commie stooge.

01:33:19.320 --> 01:33:20.912
Burt Gurney has
left the country.

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:23.594
The cell he was part of has
been smashed by the police.

01:33:24.200 --> 01:33:25.269
Might have thought
he was credible

01:33:25.360 --> 01:33:27.828
because he's Mr. Laurentz's
current protg,

01:33:29.040 --> 01:33:32.032
but you don't want to be seen as
Burt Gurney's mouthpiece after this.

01:33:33.080 --> 01:33:35.150
How did you know
Burt was my source?

01:33:35.320 --> 01:33:36.673
Late last night,
I talked to Laurence,

01:33:36.760 --> 01:33:38.557
put two and two together.

01:33:38.720 --> 01:33:41.314
Well, no reason to send this
since I ran into you.

01:33:41.640 --> 01:33:44.200
It's my way of apology for
Thessaly horning in last night.

01:33:44.360 --> 01:33:46.157
I do value
our friendship, Thora,

01:33:46.320 --> 01:33:48.151
but I'm late for
something important.

01:33:51.240 --> 01:33:52.240
(GOAT BLEATING)

01:33:52.600 --> 01:33:54.192
(WOMAN SOBBING)

01:34:06.840 --> 01:34:07.840
(THUNDER RUMBLES)

01:34:09.440 --> 01:34:13.353
Why on your knees before
this Hebrew, Autolochus?

01:34:13.520 --> 01:34:16.080
I encountered him
before, Gracchus.

01:34:16.240 --> 01:34:18.549
Beside the well
of Jehosaphat.

01:34:20.680 --> 01:34:22.557
And what manner of man.

01:34:22.760 --> 01:34:24.432
He's a priest of
the Israelites,

01:34:24.520 --> 01:34:26.511
despised even by
the other priests.

01:34:26.720 --> 01:34:27.869
No.

01:34:28.520 --> 01:34:30.351
On yesterday's march,

01:34:30.880 --> 01:34:33.075
punished by the
dust of the road,

01:34:33.240 --> 01:34:35.276
I sought to drink
first at the well,

01:34:35.480 --> 01:34:36.993
before the slaves
in my charge,

01:34:37.080 --> 01:34:39.753
whose thirst was far
greater than my own.

01:34:39.920 --> 01:34:42.070
A Roman drinks
before a slave.

01:34:42.280 --> 01:34:44.077
This man was
giving water to all.

01:34:44.440 --> 01:34:47.273
He saw no Roman,
he saw no slave.

01:34:47.440 --> 01:34:51.797
He saw only men, weak men,
and gave succor.

01:34:52.920 --> 01:34:56.276
He saw suffering,
which he sought to ease.

01:34:56.440 --> 01:34:58.715
He saw sin,
and gave love.

01:34:59.320 --> 01:35:01.117
Love, Autolochus?

01:35:02.080 --> 01:35:04.514
He saw my own sin,
Gracchus, and greed.

01:35:04.960 --> 01:35:09.112
But in his eyes, I saw
no shadow of reproach.

01:35:10.280 --> 01:35:12.077
I saw only light.

01:35:12.920 --> 01:35:14.638
The light of God.

01:35:15.160 --> 01:35:17.469
You mean,
of the gods.

01:35:18.160 --> 01:35:21.197
I do not, friend Gracchus.

01:35:21.280 --> 01:35:23.840
This Hebrew is
a son of the one God.

01:35:24.000 --> 01:35:26.468
The God of this
far-flung tribe.

01:35:27.120 --> 01:35:30.157
And why shouldn't
God's anointed appear here

01:35:30.600 --> 01:35:33.751
among these strange people,
to shoulder their sins?

01:35:34.480 --> 01:35:39.554
Here, Gracchus,
in this sun-drenched land.

01:35:40.000 --> 01:35:42.468
Why should He
not take this form,

01:35:43.040 --> 01:35:44.951
the form of
an ordinary man?

01:35:45.120 --> 01:35:47.315
A man bringing us
not the old truths,

01:35:48.320 --> 01:35:49.799
but a new one.

01:35:51.480 --> 01:35:52.993
A new truth?

01:35:53.160 --> 01:35:56.357
AUTOLOCHUS: A truth beyond
the truth that we can see.

01:35:56.880 --> 01:35:59.314
A truth beyond this world.

01:35:59.840 --> 01:36:03.992
A truth told not in words,
but in light.

01:36:04.560 --> 01:36:07.950
A truth that we could see
if we had but...

01:36:08.880 --> 01:36:10.996
If we had but...

01:36:13.680 --> 01:36:16.194
Cut! Cut! "Faith!
Have but faith!"

01:36:16.360 --> 01:36:18.555
(BELL RINGING)
"Faith."

01:36:18.720 --> 01:36:20.631
"Faith. Faith!"
God damn it!

01:36:20.800 --> 01:36:21.994
Go one again.
Isn't it...

01:36:22.160 --> 01:36:23.195
They changed it.

01:36:23.360 --> 01:36:25.351
You got most of it, man.
You're all right.

01:36:25.680 --> 01:36:27.750
All right, hang on.
(SIGHS)

01:36:27.920 --> 01:36:29.990
Can I get a pat down?
I'm sweating like a pig in this thing.

01:36:30.080 --> 01:36:31.080
Ah, son of a bitch!

01:36:34.240 --> 01:36:35.240
(SIGHS)

01:36:38.040 --> 01:36:40.076
Bless me, Father,
for I have sinned.

01:36:40.880 --> 01:36:43.519
How long since your
last confession, my son?

01:36:43.680 --> 01:36:47.036
It's been,
what, 27 hours.

01:36:49.680 --> 01:36:51.830
It's really
too often, my son.

01:36:52.000 --> 01:36:53.194
You're not
that bad.

01:36:53.360 --> 01:36:55.112
I don't know, Father.

01:36:55.280 --> 01:36:58.431
I snuck a cigarette.
Or two.

01:36:59.200 --> 01:37:01.555
I didn't make it home
in time for dinner.

01:37:04.640 --> 01:37:05.640
(SIGHS)

01:37:06.120 --> 01:37:08.793
And I, uh, struck
a movie star in anger.

01:37:12.720 --> 01:37:14.073
All right.

01:37:14.240 --> 01:37:16.071
Five Hail Marys.

01:37:16.920 --> 01:37:18.273
Okay.

01:37:19.240 --> 01:37:20.593
Okay.

01:37:21.600 --> 01:37:22.919
Father?

01:37:23.880 --> 01:37:25.199
Yes, my son.

01:37:25.400 --> 01:37:27.550
May I ask you
something, Father?

01:37:29.800 --> 01:37:31.472
Of course, my son.

01:37:35.960 --> 01:37:38.428
If there's something
that's easy,

01:37:39.400 --> 01:37:41.550
is that wrong?

01:37:42.280 --> 01:37:43.395
Easy?

01:37:43.560 --> 01:37:45.755
Yeah, easy to do.

01:37:45.960 --> 01:37:47.632
Easy to...

01:37:47.840 --> 01:37:49.239
Like, an easy job.

01:37:49.400 --> 01:37:52.233
No, it's not a bad job.
It's not bad.

01:37:55.280 --> 01:38:00.229
But, then, there's this other
job that's not so easy.

01:38:00.400 --> 01:38:03.119
No, in fact, it's hard.

01:38:03.280 --> 01:38:04.633
It's so hard, Father...

01:38:04.800 --> 01:38:07.473
Sometimes I don't know
if I can keep doing it,

01:38:08.640 --> 01:38:10.471
but it seems right.

01:38:12.960 --> 01:38:14.951
I don't know
how to explain.

01:38:19.800 --> 01:38:22.633
God wants us to
do what's right.

01:38:27.160 --> 01:38:28.354
Yeah.

01:38:30.000 --> 01:38:31.638
Yeah, of course
He does.

01:38:31.840 --> 01:38:34.718
The inner voice that
tells you what's right,

01:38:34.880 --> 01:38:37.474
it comes from God,
my son.

01:38:37.680 --> 01:38:38.795
Yeah, I got it.

01:38:38.960 --> 01:38:40.313
That's His way
of saying that...

01:38:40.480 --> 01:38:41.993
Yeah, yeah,
I got it.

01:38:42.160 --> 01:38:43.673
NATALIE: Still raining
in Gallup, New Mexico.

01:38:43.840 --> 01:38:45.114
And the Tucumcari crew
has shot all the plates

01:38:45.200 --> 01:38:46.474
we need for
Came the Rain.

01:38:46.640 --> 01:38:49.240
Well, just shoot the showdown in
the weather and we'll retitle it.

01:38:49.280 --> 01:38:52.716
Tucumcari Tempest,
Desert Squall, Hold Back The Storm.

01:38:52.880 --> 01:38:55.235
NARRATOR: The stories begin,
the stories end.

01:38:55.400 --> 01:38:56.674
I don't know,
bounce it off the writers.

01:38:56.840 --> 01:38:57.840
NARRATOR: So it has been.

01:38:57.880 --> 01:38:58.915
Here's today's
call list.

01:38:59.000 --> 01:39:01.514
Add a call to a Mr. Cuddahy
at the Lockheed Corporation.

01:39:01.680 --> 01:39:03.033
Long call?
Short?

01:39:03.200 --> 01:39:05.077
"Thanks, but no thanks."
How long was that?

01:39:05.240 --> 01:39:06.434
NARRATOR: But the story
of Eddie Mannix...

01:39:06.520 --> 01:39:07.748
Who do we
call first?

01:39:07.840 --> 01:39:09.193
...will never end.

01:39:09.280 --> 01:39:10.429
New York first.

01:39:10.520 --> 01:39:11.800
Time to check in
with Mr. Schenk.

01:39:11.920 --> 01:39:16.869
NARRATOR: For his is a tale
written in light everlasting.

